[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to this repertoire!"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]


{ Hello and welcome aboard! I'm so excited to share with you the opening system that got me from a 12-year-old beginner to a National Master. The fact that it can be used against king's pawn opening [ 1.e4 ], all 1.d4 setups including the London System, the English Opening [ 1.c4 ], and anything else White plays made it my only weapon as Black. And yes, I still use it all the time when I play online or over the board. I would like to give you a special thanks for taking the time to go over this introduction chapter. Here you will learn how even though I started Chess late, the opening system you are about to learn was all I needed to make it to master level with very little memorization. I will also tell you more about why I picked it and why I never replaced it. Lastly, you must understand how although this setup works against anything White plays, we still need to be able to tell when we are facing the king's pawn opening [ 1.e4 ] or something else. My first visit to the local Chess academy in Artemisa, Cuba was at the age of 12. When I got there, they already had a group of players who had been training together for years. According to the head coach, I was a bit old to get into competitive Chess since they typically looked for kids between the ages of 5 and 9. Compared to someone who started that young, I was indeed behind. Of course, he didn't tell me this until many years later, but he certainly did not want to invest time and energy on me. I was given a tactics book to work on my own at the back of the room. I could only join the rest of the students once they were done with their lesson to play blitz [5 minute games]. This continued for four months until it was time to compete to see who would represent Artemisa in the State scholastic championship. That's when the head coach of the academy sat with me to talk about an opening repertoire. He showed me a few openings for Black, but he already knew which one I was going to pick. Before visiting the academy, I knew the basics of the game from playing in my neighborhood with other novice players. They often forgot about my hidden bishops from far away [like the g7-bishop in the current position]. Once in the academy, I continued developing my bishops in such a way. It's called a fianchetto. So, when I saw an opening with such a component, I chose it. It happened to be the Pirc Defense. Of course, my coach had stronger reasons for introducing me to the hypermodern movement! Hypermodern? Yes, we will talk about it later in the course. First, let's review why my coach thought this was the opening for someone who started Chess 'late'. a] It is a system. This means one only needs to know where the pieces go and the typical plans. Move order is not that relevant and that reduces the amount of theory one has to memorize. b] It can be played even if White does not start with 1.e4 . In such cases, we call it King's Indian Defense [KID] instead of Pirc Defense, but the setup is the same. This means we don't need to learn a separate opening to face the queen's pawn opening [ 1.d4 ] for example. c] Although elite players such as Magnus Carlsen and Vladimir Kramnik have used the Pirc Defense, it is not so popular. So, a lot of players are not familiar with it. Even at the master level, I always feel like I'm bringing my opponents into my territory. d] I don't want you to, but this opening system could also be played as White. I hope you pick something else as White so that you learn more Chess in general, but know you have that option. It could look something like this: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d3 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 e6 4.Bg2 Be7 5.O-O and so on. This could occur from a variety of move-orders, including after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.Nf3 . But again, I don't recommend playing this way as White to avoid becoming a one-note chess player. My experience with this repertoire: With this opening system for Black, I made the team for my hometown. Then, thanks to my results in the state championships, I was offered to join a school of Chess where training was more intense than what we had at the local academy. I was there for 3 years until my family decided to move to the United States. By then, I had been training consistently and playing one or two tournaments a year, but I didn't have any rating yet. Rated tournaments were not so abundant back then. Why am I telling you all this? Well, once in the U.S., I did not play Chess for years. However, once in college, I decided to play a few tournaments. Since Pirc/KID is all about the main ideas and plans, I was able to utilize it without much preparation and after a few tournaments, I got the National Master title. Of course, we cannot attribute it to my opening repertoire only, but it certainly helped to always be in my elements and get to the middlegame comfortably. Why did I make this course? I have been teaching Chess for over 10 years now and I've learned a great deal about what beginners want in order to take their game to the next level. I also know that what they typically want is the opposite of what they need. I don't teach the same opening to every student I work with. At the end of the day, we are all different and we need an opening we connect with and enjoy. However, my formula to take beginners to the next level is simple: 10 % Opening [understand the ideas behind your moves] 75 % Tactics [solve as many puzzles as possible] 10 % Strategy & positional Chess 5% Basic endgames [basic checkmates + basic king & pawns] This and playing games consistently over a long period of time [length depends on talent and other factors] never fails. The key word is consistency of course. Every time any of my students learns a new opening from a book or course, they expect the author to cover every single line their opponent could play. They want to be handheld all the way. However, due to the nature of Chess, that is impossible. The good news is that since we chose a system, we can apply the same plans to anything White plays. For example, once you cover the chapter titledPirc vs. Classical Variation, you will have the most important plans in this opening system and with them, you can start playing and getting familiarized with your new opening. However, learning the other variations is crucial too since they show you more specific and effective plans to deal with the trickiest setups White can adopt. Please, don't aim to memorize everything. Just learn the initial moves and typical ideas. Then, you start using it. If you encounter a variation you forgot, refer back to this course and review it. With that said, here is what I want you to keep in mind as you go through this course: a] If White starts with the move 1.e4 , our system is called Pirc Defense. b] If White starts with the move 1.d4 [or anything other than 1.e4 , ] our system is called King's Indian Defense [KID] and middlegame plans might be slightly different. c] After many years playing and teaching this opening system, I can tell you it's way more common to encounter 1.e4 than 1.d4 at the beginner and intermediate levels. For that reason, I would focus more on the Pirc Defense chapters. The other White opening you'll encounter often is theLondon System. So, review that chapter well too. I hope you enjoy the course and are able to use this fighting repertoire for the rest of your chess career! }
