[Result "*"]


{ Here is a glossary of some chess terms relevant to this repertoire. When
these terms first arise in the course, you can click them to see their
definition here. You can also click the terms from here to navigate to an example from the course. Fianchetto: The term for the placement of a bishop
on a long diagonal - specifically the b2, g2, g7, or b7 squares. From here, they have great scope and aggressive possibilities. Flank Pawn: A pawn on the edge of the board, as opposed to the center. Typically these are the a, b, g, & h-pawns. In the middlegame, these can be pushed to aid in an
attack. Fork: Also called a double attack, when a piece attacks more than one of the opponent's pieces at the same time. Hypermodern: An approach to the opening that emerged after World War 1 by pioneer Aron Nimzowitsch that involves conceding the center and attacking it from the sides with minor pieces, and only later striking in the center with a pawn. Leverage Pawn: When attacking with pawns on one side of the board, it can be useful to start with a pawn move up one square to support a future push by an adjacent pawn. The supporting pawn can be called a Leverage Pawn. In this
course, ...c6 will be a common leverage pawn move, preparing the aggressive ...b5 advance. Prophylaxis The concept of stopping your opponent's idea before proceeding with your own. Thematic: A term to describe a normal idea, maneuver, or piece arrangement in a given opening that is useful to know and repeat in your own games. Tempo: A term used to measure time and development in chess, often in the opening. If a white knight develops from its starting square and attacks the enemy queen at the same time, White is gaining a tempo since the queen likely must spend another move to retreat. This can also apply in other stages of the game. Transposition: An alternative move-order that reaches the same position as from another move order. In other words, different routes to the same destination. }
