{ What is the most important part of the Chess board? Before learning any
openings, we need to know the answer to this question. Yes, we are talking
about the center. More specifically the squares e4, e5, d4 and d5 . } 1.e4
{ Now you understand why White typically starts by moving their central
pawns. Of course they want to control the most important part of the
battlefield. On the other hand, Black wants the opposite! } 1...d6
{ Ashypermodern players, we would love to start by moving our knight from
g8 to f6. That way, we immediately threaten their e4-pawn. Yes, that's what
we like to do! However, that same pawn could advance putting our knight in danger. For that reason, we first play 1...d6. }
2.d4
{ Just like that! White is so happy to have full control over the center. }
2...Nf6
{ As early as in move #2, we can fully appreciate whathypermodern openings
are all about. We allow our opponent to build a solid pawn center
[White's e4 and d4 pawns] only to attack it with our knights and bishops [also known as minor
pieces]. } 3.Nc3
{ This time, White plays the main move. Notice how their knight develops by
protecting the vulnerable e4-pawn. } 3...g6
{ Now that White reacted to our previous threat
[Nxe4], we prepare to put our f8-bishop inside
thefianchetto [g7]. From there, it will be eyeing the center. }
4.Nf3
{ After White's fourth move, we are officially facing the classical
variation. In my mind, this means no stress! } 4...Bg7
{ I love this bishop hiding inside the fianchetto. So many opponents forget
about it. } 5.Bd3
{ In this variation, White develops their light-squared bishop to d3
avoiding Black's central fork [seeprevious line with 5.Bc4
] . } 5...O-O
{ White's last move still means no stress, so we take a moment to put our
king in safety. } 6.O-O
{ I can see you getting sad already because we don't have the centralfork.
Well, let me introduce you to my favorite plan against the Classical
setup... } 6...Bg4
{ I've used this move vs. anything in the Classical: 5. Bc4 5. Bd3 or 5.
Be2. Fewer plans to remember! We want to neutralize the f3-knight! Sure,
but why? a] now White feels pressured and if that knight moves, we get their queen b] eliminating the f3-knight leaves
their d4-pawn hanging in the center [our target] c] the f3-knight is preventing us from striking the center with thethematic ...e5 push. }
7.h3 Bxf3 { Our bishop did its part —good bye, knight! } 8.Qxf3
{ Do we play ...e5 now? No! White's d4-pawn is not protected anymore. White
could also play 8.gxf3 but it would ruin their pawn structure and expose
their king. } 8...Nc6
{ It's so nice to develop our pieces with atempo! Now White has two ways to
react to our threat [...Nxd4]. Option 1 is to
advance their pawn to safety 9.d5 Option 2 is to develop their final minor piece 9.Be3 and keep their center stable. Notice how our c6-knight attacks
their d4-pawn and supports our ...e5 push. } 9.d5
{ As I mentioned earlier, we like when our opponents break their perfect
center. Now, the d4 and e5 squares belong to us. } 9...Ne5
{ I remember this as the dark-square strategy because we play on the dark
squares in the center. You will see how our pieces typically play around
the d4, e5 and c5 squares. } 10.Qg3
{ If you make it this far, the rest is easy. First, you can eliminate their
d3-bishop any time by playing Nxd3. Second, we have to target their central
pawns again. Now ...c6 is the way to go as it also opens your mighty queen to move to the active a5-square. Third, never forget about your hidden but
powerful fianchettoed bishop. } 10...c6
{ Time to talk about the middlegame! a] queen wants to go to
a5 b] a8-rook wants to go to the c-file
[Rc8] c] f6-knight can go to d7 to open our fianchettoed bishop and eventually land on the dark c5-square.
Yes, we talk about the dark square strategy again and again. A possible continuation is 11.f4 Nxd3 12.Qxd3 cxd5 happy to trade our flank pawn for one of White's central pawns. }
*

