but why? a] now White feels pressured and if that knight moves, we get their queen b] eliminating the f3-knight leaves
their d4-pawn hanging in the center [our target] c] the f3-knight is preventing us from striking the center with thethematic ...e5 push. }
7.h3 Bxf3 { Our bishop did its part —good bye, knight! } 8.Qxf3
{ Do we play ...e5 now? No! White's d4-pawn is not protected anymore. White
could also play 8.gxf3 but it would ruin their pawn structure and expose
their king. } 8...Nc6
{ It's so nice to develop our pieces with atempo! Now White has two ways to
react to our threat [...Nxd4]. Option 1 is to
advance their pawn to safety 9.d5 Option 2 is to develop their final minor piece 9.Be3 and keep their center stable. Notice how our c6-knight attacks
their d4-pawn and supports our ...e5 push. } 9.Be3
{ This is the most natural move since it completes development and keeps
their center stable. Now the c6-knight cannot jump to d4 or e5. So, what do
we do? } 9...Nd7
{ I feel so hypermodern now — pressure on their central pawns from far
away! Joking aside, it's a tricky style and many players don't know how to
handle it. White might not even notice the bishop is now attacking their d4-pawn too. Inexperienced players tend to push their d-pawn leaving the
same weaknesses on d4 and e5. We will talk more about that premature push soon. }
10.d5
{ Again? Well, you should be happy to see this move by now. Let's test if
your overall Chess is improving. What came to mind when you saw White's
pawn push? I hope it was one of the following: a] the dark square strategy b] every time we push a pawn in Chess,
weaknesses are created c] fork. } 10...Nce5
{ Black is ready to eliminate the d3-bishop and play c6 to challenge
White's central pawn [d5]. A possible
continuation is 11.Qe2 c6 12.dxc6 bxc6 [replacing the important c6-pawn to keep the c3-knight away] 13.f4 Nxd3 and
yes, similar ideas for the middlegame: a] queen wants to go to a5 b] a8-rook wants to go to the b-file since it's now open c] d7-knight is waiting to jump to e5 or c5 }
*

