[White "1) Pirc vs. Classical Variation"]
[Black "Classical Variation: 5.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B08"]


{ What is the most important part of the Chess board? Before learning any
openings, we need to know the answer to this question. Yes, we are talking
about the center. More specifically the squares e4, e5, d4 and d5 . } 1.e4
{ Now you understand why White typically starts by moving their central
pawns. Of course they want to control the most important part of the
battlefield. On the other hand, Black wants the opposite! } 1...d6
{ Ashypermodern players, we would love to start by moving our knight from
g8 to f6. That way, we immediately threaten their e4-pawn. Yes, that's what
we like to do! However, that same pawn could advance putting our knight in danger. For that reason, we first play 1...d6. }
2.d4
{ Just like that! White is so happy to have full control over the center. }
2...Nf6
{ As early as in move #2, we can fully appreciate whathypermodern openings
are all about. We allow our opponent to build a solid pawn center
[White's e4 and d4 pawns] only to attack it with our knights and bishops [also known as minor
pieces]. } 3.Nc3
{ This time, White plays the main move. Notice how their knight develops by
protecting the vulnerable e4-pawn. } 3...g6
{ Now that White reacted to our previous threat
[Nxe4], we prepare to put our f8-bishop inside
thefianchetto [g7]. From there, it will be eyeing the center. }
4.Nf3
{ After White's fourth move, we are officially facing the classical
variation. In my mind, this means no stress! } 4...Bg7
{ I love this bishop hiding inside the fianchetto. So many opponents forget
about it. } 5.h3
{ It's time to introduce you to the concept ofprophylaxis. As you face more
experienced opponents, they will be familiar with our Bg4 move. If they
don't like it, they could prevent it by moving their pawn to h3 on move #5. }
5...O-O
{ As sophisticated as h3 might look, in my mind it still means no stress.
So, I take a moment to put my king in safety. } 6.Bd3
{ Here we are again facing that Bd3 line, but we cannot play Bg4. What
then? Well, as a hypermodern player, only one question should come to mind.
How do I bother White's central pawns? I want to whistle at them. I want to throw rocks at them. Anything to make them feel the pressure! }
6...Nc6
{ Yes, the same knight attacking the dark squares in the center. This time,
we want to put our e-pawn on e5 as soon as possible; and with our knight on
c6, we are finally ready. } 7.O-O
{ White could have responded to our provocation by playing 7.d5 , but this
time let's see what happens if they simply castle. } 7...e5
{ Get used to this ...e5 break. It's one of our main plans to claim our
share of the center. Now White can take, advance or defend. Let's review
8.dxe5 first. } 8.dxe5 Nxe5
{ Why do we take with knight instead of pawn? Another typical move in
Black's middlegame plan is to put our pawn on c6. That way, we keep their
c3-knight from coming into our territory with Nd5 or Nb5. As you can see, now c6 is available for our c7-pawn. }
9.Nxe5 dxe5 10.Bg5 Be6
{ Time to talk about our middlegame plan: a] c-pawn wants to
go to c6 to control d5 and b5 b] Queen belongs on c7 to
connect our rooks and defend the e5-pawn c] h6 would be nice to remove their annoying g5-bishop d] our a8-rook belongs on
d8 to control the open d-file } *

