{ What is the most important part of the Chess board? Before learning any
openings, we need to know the answer to this question. Yes, we are talking
about the center. More specifically the squares e4, e5, d4 and d5 . } 1.e4
{ Now you understand why White typically starts by moving their central
pawns. Of course they want to control the most important part of the
battlefield. On the other hand, Black wants the opposite! } 1...d6
{ Ashypermodern players, we would love to start by moving our knight from
g8 to f6. That way, we immediately threaten their e4-pawn. Yes, that's what
we like to do! However, that same pawn could advance putting our knight in danger. For that reason, we first play 1...d6. }
2.d4
{ Just like that! White is so happy to have full control over the center. }
2...Nf6
{ As early as in move #2, we can fully appreciate whathypermodern openings
are all about. We allow our opponent to build a solid pawn center
[White's e4 and d4 pawns] only to attack it with our knights and bishops [also known as minor
pieces]. } 3.Nc3
{ This time, White plays the main move. Notice how their knight develops by
protecting the vulnerable e4-pawn. } 3...g6
{ Now that White reacted to our previous threat
[Nxe4], we prepare to put our f8-bishop inside
thefianchetto [g7]. From there, it will be eyeing the center. }
4.Nf3
{ After White's fourth move, we are officially facing the classical
variation. In my mind, this means no stress! } 4...Bg7
{ I love this bishop hiding inside the fianchetto. So many opponents forget
about it. } 5.h3
{ It's time to introduce you to the concept ofprophylaxis. As you face more
experienced opponents, they will be familiar with our Bg4 move. If they
don't like it, they could prevent it by moving their pawn to h3 on move #5. }
5...O-O
{ As sophisticated as h3 might look, in my mind it still means no stress.
So, I take a moment to put my king in safety. } 6.Bd3
{ Here we are again facing that Bd3 line, but we cannot play Bg4. What
then? Well, as a hypermodern player, only one question should come to mind.
How do I bother White's central pawns? I want to whistle at them. I want to throw rocks at them. Anything to make them feel the pressure! }
6...Nc6
{ Yes, the same knight attacking the dark squares in the center. This time,
we want to put our e-pawn on e5 as soon as possible; and with our knight on
c6, we are finally ready. } 7.O-O
{ White could have responded to our provocation by playing 7.d5 , but this
time let's see what happens if they simply castle. } 7...e5
{ Get used to this ...e5 break. It's one of our main plans to claim our
share of the center. Now White can take, advance or defend. Here we will
look at the advance. } 8.d5
{ No, this is not the moment to smile... Not yet. White pushed their
d-pawn, but they are following sound chess principles this time. When our
central pawns are next to each other controlling the center, we don't want to push them unless we are challenged by an enemy pawn. It's in
White's interest to advance to avoid the possibility of the e5-square becoming vacant for the black minor pieces [knights and bishops] if we ever decide to capture on d4. For example, in a line like this: 8.Be3 exd4 9.Nxd4 Nxd4 10.Bxd4 Re8 Black is doing very
well with excellent control of the e5-square. } 8...Ne7
{ Please, don't get overwhelmed yet. It might seem like our c6-knight moves
to a random square every time we review a new variation, but it's not like
that. Let's connect the dots: In general, when we have a locked center [notice how the four central pawns are stuck], we
must attack on the flanks. How do we know what flank is best for us? Easy! Our pawn chain is aiming at it. The c7-d6-e5 pawns are pointing towards the kingside. }
9.Be3
{ White pieces have e4-d5 pointing at the queenside. For this reason, they
should attack on that side of the board. I see, but why? Well, it comes
down to this. Thanks to our own central pawns, we simply have more space on a particular side of the board. And yes, this is another general Chess
principle. } 9...Ne8
{ What is this now? Get ready for more Chess wisdom. When it's time to
expand on our flank, we want to target the pawn in front of our most
forward pawn. Our most forward pawn now is e5. The pawn in front of it is e4. Well, we need to play f5 in order to target it. The only other thing
you have to do is bring as many pieces as possible to the kingside. } 10.a4
f5
{ Hey Robert, I don't mean to bother, but isn't our king getting a bit
exposed? First, our fianchettoed bishop is acting like a pawn too. Second,
as long as the center is locked, White won't be able to open up lines and attack our king. So, keep that center locked! Also, if they play 11.exf5
you can recapture however you like, but I prefer to use the g6-pawn. 11...gxf5 Soon you will see a game I played using this line. In the interim, here is a possible continuation 11.b4 f4 [the pawn storm] 12.Bd2 g5 13.Nxg5 Nxd5 14.exd5 Qxg5 and now everything is
set to hunt the white king. You will love the game I'm about to show you! }
