1.e4 d6
{ Ashypermodern players, we would love to start by moving our knight from
g8 to f6. That way, we immediately threaten their e4-pawn. Yes, that's what
we like to do! However, that same pawn could advance putting our knight in danger. For that reason, we first play 1...d6. }
2.d4 Nf6
{ As early as in move #2, we can fully appreciate whathypermodern openings
are all about. We allow our opponent to build a solid pawn center
[White's e4 and d4 pawns] only to attack it with our knights and bishops [also known as minor
pieces]. } 3.Bd3
{ A different way to protect the e4-pawn. Something about my beginner
students when they learn a new opening is that they expect their opponents
to play exactly what they learned. However, with so many possible moves in Chess, that's often not the case. }
3...g6
{ Good news is we know where our pieces belong regardless of what White
plays (unless they do something aggressive) . } 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.O-O O-O
{ Kingside development is complete. } 6.Re1 Bg4
{ You know this plan by now. And yes, I could have also played 6...Nc6 or
6...c6 . } 7.h3 Bxf3 8.Qxf3
{ Recapturing with the g-pawn would ruin White's pawn structure and expose
their king. } 8...Nc6 { Again — we develop with a tempo. } 9.c3 e5
{ Opening phase is complete now that we stroke the center with the thematic
...e5 push. } 10.d5
{ The four central pawns are locked. Time to pick your flank and transfer
our knight from the unsafe c6-square to it. } 10...Ne7
{ Getting ready to target the pawn in front of our most forward pawn. } 11.c4
{ White knew these principles too! } 11...Nd7
{ Notice how I moved my knight from f6 to d7 this time. I have also moved
it to e8 in other games. It's mostly a matter of taste. We mainly want to
free our f7-pawn. } 12.Nc3 f5 13.Qd1 f4 14.f3 g5 { Pawn storm! } 15.b4 h5
{ Once we played f4, that f-pawn became our most forward pawn. So, now we
target the white pawn in front of it [f3]. }
16.Bd2 Ng6 { All my pieces want to go to the kingside. } 17.Be2 Nf6
{ Let's go! } 18.a4 Rf7
{ Thematic plan at this point. I want my rook on the same file as the white
king and it also helps my g-pawn break on g4. } 19.c5 Bf8
{ Yes, even our dark-squared bishop that seemed to be bad has an important
role in our plan. It moves to support our center while leaving g7 available
for the f7-rook. } 20.cxd6 cxd6
{ We recapture with a pawn to keep the center locked. } 21.Rc1 Rg7
{ Our maneuver is complete! } 22.Nb5 a6
{ I don't like enemy pieces in my territory. We typically don't move pawns
where we are being attacked, but here it comes with a tempo on the
b5-knight. } 23.Nc3 Nh4 { Our infiltration begins. } 24.Kh1 Qe8
{ Our queen transfers from queenside to kingside. } 25.a5 Qg6
{ The black queen arrived and the party may begin! } 26.Rg1 g4
{ We finally made contact. Black's main objective now is to open up lines
for their pieces to attack. } 27.Be1 g3
{ I know I'm doing the opposite of opening up lines. However, since I'm
familiar with these positions, I knew it was only preparation for the final
blow. } 28.Na4 Nh7
{ My knight is going for the h3 pawn and everybody knows it. That's how we
open the kingside again. } 29.Nb6 Rd8 30.Rc8 Rxc8 31.Nxc8 Ng5
{ It's coming! } 32.Nb6 Nxh3 { I was not kidding. } 33.gxh3
{ Black to move and there is a forced mate in 3 moves. Can you find it? }
33...g2+ 34.Kh2
{ Come on! There is mate in 2 moves now. Did you already see it? } 34...Qg3+
35.Bxg3 fxg3#
{ Checkmate! Our knight protects the g2-pawn while our rook protects the g3
pawn. Besides the interesting mate, pay attention to White's queenside
expansion. It did not succeed because they had to react to our pawn storm on the other flank. }
*

