{ What is the most important part of the Chess board? Before learning any
openings, we need to know the answer to this question. Yes, we are talking
about the center. More specifically the squares e4, e5, d4 and d5 . } 1.e4
{ Now you understand why White typically starts by moving their central
pawns. Of course they want to control the most important part of the
battlefield. On the other hand, Black wants the opposite! } 1...d6
{ Ashypermodern players, we would love to start by moving our knight from
g8 to f6. That way, we immediately threaten their e4-pawn. Yes, that's what
we like to do! However, that same pawn could advance putting our knight in danger. For that reason, we first play 1...d6. }
2.d4
{ Just like that! White is so happy to have full control over the center. }
2...Nf6
{ As early as in move #2, we can fully appreciate whathypermodern openings
are all about. We allow our opponent to build a solid pawn center
[White's e4 and d4 pawns] only to attack it with our knights and bishops [also known as minor
pieces]. } 3.Nc3
{ This time, White plays the main move. Notice how their knight develops by
protecting the vulnerable e4-pawn. } 3...g6
{ Now that White reacted to our previous threat
[Nxe4], we prepare to put our f8-bishop inside
thefianchetto [g7]. From there, it will be eyeing the center. }
4.Nf3
{ After White's fourth move, we are officially facing the classical
variation. In my mind, this means no stress! } 4...Bg7
{ I love this bishop hiding inside the fianchetto. So many opponents forget
about it. } 5.Be2
{ That's new. Is it dangerous? No! Then, we keep going with our setup. }
5...O-O { Kingside development is complete. } 6.O-O c6
{ So far we have learned the central fork when the white bishop is
developed to c4. We also learned the Bg4 pin when White moves their bishop
to d3. However, with this ultra passive move [Be2], the central fork is impossible while Bg4 is less effective.
Also, this c6 move will be present in so many other variations. So, pay attention! a] we already know our c6-pawn keeps their c3-knight from entering our territory [d5 and b5]. b] it also makes the c7-square available for our
queen. } 7.h3
{ White can also play 7.e5 dxe5 8.dxe5 Qxd1 9.Rxd1 Ng4 10.Bf4 Nd7 and now
the e5-pawn is under heavy attack. } 7...Nbd7
{ We want our thematic ...e5 break. For that, we need the help of our
knight. Since c6 is occupied by one of our own pawns, we develop it to d7.
} 8.Bg5 { White's last minor piece is developed. } 8...e5
{ Black finally strikes the center. } 9.Qd2 Qc7
{ Yes, you already knew the black queen belongs on c7. } 10.dxe5 dxe5
{ Middlegame plan: a] d7-knight wants to go to either d4 or f4
supported by our e5-pawn. b] c8-bishop then comes out to e6
c] f8-rook wants to go to e8 and the a8-rook goes to d8. Note: this 6...c6 plan can be played vs. 5. Bc4 and 5. Bd3 too for simplicity. }
*

