[Nxe4], we prepare to put our f8-bishop inside
thefianchetto [g7]. From there, it will be eyeing the center. }
4.Nf3
{ After White's fourth move, we are officially facing the classical
variation. In my mind, this means no stress! } 4...Bg7
{ I love this bishop hiding inside the fianchetto. So many opponents forget
about it. } 5.Be2
{ That's new. Is it dangerous? No! Then, we keep going with our setup. }
5...O-O { Kingside development is complete. } 6.O-O c6
{ So far we have learned the central fork when the white bishop is
developed to c4. We also learned the Bg4 pin when White moves their bishop
to d3. However, with this ultra passive move [Be2], the central fork is impossible while Bg4 is less effective.
Also, this c6 move will be present in so many other variations. So, pay attention! a] we already know our c6-pawn keeps their c3-knight from entering our territory [d5 and b5]. b] it also makes the c7-square available for our
queen. } 7.h3
{ White can also play 7.e5 dxe5 8.dxe5 Qxd1 9.Rxd1 Ng4 10.Bf4 Nd7 and now
the e5-pawn is under heavy attack. } 7...Nbd7
{ We want our thematic ...e5 break. For that, we need the help of our
knight. Since c6 is occupied by one of our own pawns, we develop it to d7.
} 8.e5
{ We always have to consider this aggressive move. Luckily we've been
preparing for it since move one. } 8...dxe5 { Good bye pawn! } 9.dxe5
{ Wait a second! Do we have another enemy pawn on e5? Yes, but it is only
defended by a minor piece now instead of another pawn. Once the f6-knight
moves out of danger, our fianchettoed bishop from g7 will activate. } 9...Nd5
10.Nxd5 cxd5
{ After 11.Qxd5 Nxe5 the white queen would be hanging on d5. Regarding the
middlegame plan, top priority is the development of our c8-bishop followed
by bringing our rooks to c8 and d8. } *

