1.Nf3 d6
{ This game was played years before Magnus became an elite player. However,
it was obvious he would be joining the top soon. Notice how even though
White didn't start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 , he played 1...d6 anyways in order to get
into our opening system. } 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nbd2 g6 4.e4
{ This is now officially the Pirc Defense. It's the same thing as if White
had played e4 on their first turn. As you can see, Black allows White to
fill the center with two pawns in order to attack them later with pieces and strategic pawn breaks. }
4...Bg7 5.Bd3 O-O
{ Our kingside development is complete! Now it's time to develop our
queenside minor pieces and start targeting White's central pawns. } 6.O-O Nc6
{ The hypermodern approach in action! Magnus is already putting pressure on
the white central pawns from far away. } 7.c3
{ As we will learn in this course, if instead of c3 White pushes their
d-pawn, the c6-knight moves to b4 attacking the white bishop on d3. } 7...e5
{ The thematic pawn break to claim our share of the center and make the
white central pawns unstable. } 8.h3 Nh5
{ Black's h5-knight is ready to land on f4. Likewise, now the fianchettoed
bishop is open from g7, which puts more pressure on White's d4-pawn
[it's all about White's center]. How can you not like this move? }
9.dxe5 Nf4
{ These kinds of moves is what separates experienced from inexperienced
players. Black got their knight to a good square with a tempo on the
d3-bishop. They know the e5-pawn is not going anywhere! You know you would have captured on e5 just like me. }
10.Bb5 Nxe5 11.Nxe5 Qg5
{ Once again, Magnus resists his impulse to recapture on e5. Instead, he
improves his powerful queen by threatening checkmate on g2. } 12.Ng4 Qxb5
13.Nb3 Ne2+ 14.Kh1 Bxg4
{ Black develops their last minor piece by exposing the white king. } 15.hxg4
Rae8
{ The only black piece that was doing nothing gets activated by putting
pressure on White's central pawn. } 16.Be3 Rxe4 17.Re1 Qh5+
{ Beautiful queen sacrifice! Once White captures the black queen, the
e4-rook is open to move to h4 with a nice checkmate. 18.gxh5 Rh4# } *

