1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f3
{ Allow me to introduce you to the variation that almost made me stop
playing this opening. The f3-pawn is what we call a leverage pawn. White
basically wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm towards the castled black king. How? Easy! They want to continue with Be3, Qd2, O-O-O,
and then g4 to start attacking our king with pawns. Aggressive players enjoy this system as White because it's easy to execute and extremely powerful. Luckily, I didn't quit despite all my painful defeats. I did stick around and found an antidote instead! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Pirc vs. Opposite-Castle Attack"]
[Black "Opposite-Side Attack: 5.Be3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f3
{ Do you remember what I said about the classical variation
[ 4.Nf3? ] I told you how in my mind it means
no stress. Well, whenever I see 4. f3 or any indication that White wants to castle queenside, all I see is chaos on the horizon. }
4...c6
{ Yes, this is the antidote. White's f3-pawn is what we call a leverage
pawn. They simply want to castle queenside and start a pawn storm towards
the black king once it castles kingside. So, all we need to remember, when there is any indication of opposite-side castling attack, is the
following a] stop everything on your kingside [even Bg7] b] focus on expanding on the queenside where the white king wants to castle. }
5.Be3
{ Please, keep in mind that White could have played Be3 before f3. Just
know that f3 or queenside development are clear indications of
opposite-side castling attack [chaos]. } 5...b5
{ Now you see why we call our c6-pawn a leverage pawn. Because of it, we
could play b5 to gain space on the queenside. At the beginning of my
career, I used to play ...b5 hoping my opponent would feel scared and abort their aggressive plan. Today, I look forward to the opposite-side castle
attack. } 6.Qd2
{ White is ready to execute two key parts of their plan. First, they can
finally castle queenside. Second, their e3-bishop can move to h6 in order
to remove our kingside bishop. The good news is that we would be happy to give them our dark-squared bishop since it's not developed and we are not
castling kingside for now. Without our king castled kingside, their plan makes no sense. }
6...Nbd7 { Mobilizing our queenside pieces! } 7.O-O-O
{ The white king is finally here. Let's attack it! } 7...Qa5
{ I really like this move. From a5, our queen puts a lot of pressure on the
white king and on our opponent's head. Now we are ready to kick the
c3-knight out with 8...b4 followed by 9...Qxa2. Likewise, we are one step closer to castling queenside in case our king is no longer safe in the
center. } 8.Kb1 Nb6
{ We continue working on the queenside. Our b6-knight wants to land on c4.
If the f1-bishop captures it, we capture back with our b-pawn opening the
b-file for our a8-rook. } 9.Bh6 Bxh6 10.Qxh6 Be6
{ Now thanks to our bishop, we renewed the threat of b4 followed by Qxa2+.
In the interim, the white queen is misplaced on h6 since our king is not on
that side of the board. The black king feels safe in the center for now, but remember you can always bring it to the queenside in case of an
emergency. } *

