[White "2) Pirc vs. Opposite-Castle Attack"]
[Black "Opposite-Side Attack: 5.a4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f3
{ Do you remember what I said about the classical variation
[ 4.Nf3? ] I told you how in my mind it means
no stress. Well, whenever I see 4. f3 or any indication that White wants to castle queenside, all I see is chaos on the horizon. }
4...c6
{ Yes, this is the antidote. White's f3-pawn is what we call a leverage
pawn. They simply want to castle queenside and start a pawn storm towards
the black king once it castles kingside. So, all we need to remember, when there is any indication of opposite-side castling attack, is the
following a] stop everything on your kingside [even Bg7] b] focus on expanding on the queenside where the white king wants to castle. }
5.a4
{ This move is designed to prevent our queenside expansion with ...b5.
However, it also means the white king won't be as safe on the queenside
without their a-pawn on its home square. } 5...Nbd7
{ It's true we cannot play b5 this time, but everything else remains the
same. } 6.Be3 Qa5 7.Qd2 Bg7
{ Knowing White won't castle queenside [because of their
absent a-pawn], makes me want to get ready to castle kingside.
} 8.Bd3 e5 { Let's not forget our thematic strike in the center. } 9.Nge2 O-O
10.O-O exd4
{ Clearing the a1-h8 diagonal for our fianchetto bishop from g7. Next, we
want to: a] bring our queen to c7 b] move our
d7-knight in order to develop our c8-bishop. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Pirc vs. Opposite-Castle Attack"]
[Black "Opposite-Side Attack (Psyche!)"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be3
{ Now let's take a look at what happens if White stays flexible and has
second thoughts about going queenside. I initially didn't include this line
in the course because I've only gotten it over the board (OTB) against advanced players who know me and prepared beforehand. However, I figured it
cannot hurt for you to get some exposure to it. } 4...c6 5.Qd2 b5
{ After our ...c6-b5 approach, many white players get the hint and decide
to castle kingside. While it's not dangerous for Black, some Pirc Defense
players get confused. That's why I wanted to share this line with you. }
6.Bd3 Nbd7 7.Nf3
{ This is a clear indication that White might be considering to switch
gears and castle kingside. To continue in full
aggressive-opposite-side-attack mode, f3 should be left for their f-pawn [f3-g4-h4]. }
7...Qc7
{ Black chooses a move that is useful and flexible at the same time. We
know White might end up castling kingside after all. } 8.O-O Bg7
{ Since White castled kingside, their aggressive pawn storm isn't coming
anymore. That's why we relax and prepare to castle kingside too. } 9.Bh6 O-O
{ With both kings castled on the same side, this should be a quiet game. }
10.Bxg7 Kxg7
{ Our king keeps the white queen away from h6, and now we are perfectly
ready for ensuing play in the center and on the queenside. Notice how since
White castled kingside, any attempt at an attack on our king is far less effective. }
*

