{ I initially didn't include this line in the course because I've only
gotten it over the board (OTB) against advanced players who know me and
prepared beforehand. However, I figured it cannot hurt for you to get some exposure to it. }
1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be3 c6 5.Qd2 b5
{ After our ...c6-b5 approach, many white players get the hint and decide
to castle kingside. While it's not dangerous for Black, some Pirc Defense
players get confused. That's why I wanted to share this game with you. }
6.Bd3 Nbd7 7.Nf3
{ This is a clear indication that White might be considering to switch
gears and castle kingside. To continue in full
aggressive-opposite-side-attack mode, f3 should be left for their f-pawn [f3-g4-h4]. }
7...Qc7
{ Black chooses a move that is useful and flexible at the same time. We
know White might end up castling kingside after all. } 8.O-O Bg7
{ Since White castled kingside, their aggressive pawn storm isn't coming
anymore. That's why we relax and prepare to castle kingside too. } 9.Bh6 O-O
{ With both kings castled on the same side, this should be a quiet game. }
10.Bxg7 Kxg7 { Our king keeps the white queen away from h6. } 11.a4 b4
{ The fact that White gave up on their kingside expansion doesn't mean we
have to give up on ours. We continue to gain space on the queenside! } 12.Ne2
c5 { Ready to play 13...c4 trapping the white bishop. } 13.dxc5 dxc5 14.c3 c4
15.Bb1 Nc5
{ Our knight gets ready to land on b3 [fork] or
capture on e4. } 16.e5 Nfd7 { Counterpunching! } 17.Ned4 Nxe5 18.Nxe5 Qxe5
19.cxb4 Rd8 { Pin! Notice how everything is happening on the queenside. }
20.Nc6 Rxd2 21.Nxe5 Nb3 22.Be4 Rb8
{ If they want my rook, their knight has to come for it. } 23.Nc6 Nxa1
24.Nxb8
{ I decided to trade now because White had to capture my rook with knight
instead of bishop. Their knight is way less active now than when it was on
e5. } 24...Nb3 25.Re1 Rxb2
{ The moment I captured the b2-pawn, my c4-pawn officially became a passed
pawn and such pawns are meant to be pushed! } 26.f3 c3 27.Re3 Nd4
{ Daring my opponent to play 28.Rxc3 and then 28...Ne2+
[fork]. } 28.b5 c2 29.Bxc2 Rxc2 30.Rxe7 Ra2
31.Rxa7 Nxb5 { Tactics in the air. } 32.Ra5 Nd6 33.Ra7 Nc4 34.Nc6 Ne3 35.g4
Rg2+ 36.Kh1 Rc2
{ White resigned. Now I'm threatening checkmate
[Rc1#] or winning the c6-knight
[Rxc6]. } *

