1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be3
{ White chooses an aggressive setup! Luckily, Black has the antidote to it.
} 4...c6
{ We stop everything on the kingside to get ready for an attack on the
queenside since our opponent is likely to castle on that side of the board.
} 5.f3 b5 6.Qd2
{ White is ready to execute two key parts of their plan. First, they can
finally castle queenside. Second, their e3-bishop can move to h6 in order
to remove our kingside bishop. The good news is that we would be happy to give them our dark-squared bishop since it's not developed and we are not
castling kingside for now. Without our king castled kingside, their plan makes no sense. }
6...Nbd7 7.O-O-O Qa5
{ I really like this move. From a5, our queen puts a lot of pressure on the
white king and on our opponent's head. Now we are ready to kick the
c3-knight out with 8...b4 followed by 9...Qxa2. Likewise, we are one step closer to castling queenside in case our king is no longer safe in the
center. } 8.Kb1 Nb6 { Every black piece wants to go towards the white king! }
9.Bd3 Nc4 10.Bxc4 bxc4
{ Now the a8-rook can move to b8 to put pressure on the white king. } 11.Qe2
Ba6 12.d5 c5
{ Black knows they have a powerful attack on the queenside. There is no
need to create anything in the center. } 13.Ka1 Rb8 14.Rb1 Bg7
{ We typically develop our dark-squared bishop early in the game. This
time, we waited for the right time. Just look at that a1-h8 diagonal. Our
bishop has to be on it. } 15.Bd2 Rb4 16.Nd1 Qxa2+
{ Nice queen sacrifice. Black is ready to move their b4-rook over to a4
with checkmate. } *

