{ How dangerous is Harry, the h-pawn? Not dangerous at all if you put a
stop to it soon. We have to make sure we don't see ghosts when it's sent to
attack our fianchetto structure. I didn't think I needed to emphasize this so much, but after listening to your feedback, I understood Harry can't
be ignored. I've been playing this system for many years and that's why Harry means no stress to me, but if you are not that experienced, you'll appreciate the information in this chapter. As you will see, all we need to do is reply with ...h5 like we explained in theKID vs. Averbakh chapter,
but let's go over some examples to make sure we get comfortable with this simple but important idea. }
4...-- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Neutralizing the h-pawn Attack"]
[Black "h4 h5 in the Classical"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.h4
{ At this point, the h5-square is well protected by our g6-pawn and
f6-knight. So, we continue with our normal development. } 4...Bg7 5.Be2
{ With the white bishop on e2, we have to worry about their h5-push. So,
what do we do? We play ..h5 ourselves! } 5...h5
{ The only downside of our ...h5 move is that the g5-square becomes
available for the white pieces, but it's not really a problem. } 6.Bg5 O-O
7.Bxf6
{ I don't think anyone would take on f6, but I still wanted to mention it
for you to see how even when White really tries, they get nothing out of
their attack. } 7...Bxf6
{ 7...exf6 is possible too, but I prefer to maintain a healthy pawn
structure. } 8.g4 hxg4 9.Bxg4 Bxd4 10.Qxd4 Bxg4
{ I don't think anyone has gotten this position before, but with the white
king in the center, our b8-knight ready to move to c6 hitting the white
queen, and our superior pawn structure, I would feel very comfortable as Black. }
*

