[Black "Jobava, B. vs. Petrosian, T., European Rapid Ch. 2015"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be2 Bg7 5.h4
{ White's h-pawn is coming our way and they have enough helpers
[h1-rook, d1-queen, and e2-bishop]. } 5...h5
{ When you see a Grandmaster of Mr. Petrosian's caliber play a line or
idea, you better take notes. } 6.Nf3 O-O 7.Ng5
{ This time, White decided to occupy our g5-square with their knight. Not
ideal, but it really doesn't pose any threats. If we ever want to get rid
of it, ...Nh7 should be enough. } 7...Nc6 8.Be3 e5 9.dxe5 Nxe5 10.f3 Re8
11.Qd2 a6
{ As we learn in Chapter 2, White might castle queenside and we need to be
ready to play ...b5. ...a6 allows us to do so without weakening our
d6-pawn. } 12.a4
{ This move prevents our ...b5 push, but it also means the white king won't
be safe castling to the queenside. } 12...Bd7 13.a5 Bc6 14.Rd1 Qe7 15.O-O
{ And this is a completely equal position. It's time to play Chess! Black
played 15...Rad8 and carried on to win the game. The rest of the game is
not relevant to our course, but you can certainly find it on the internet if you'd like to see how it ended. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
