[White "Neutralizing the h-pawn Attack"]
[Black "h4 h5 in Opposite-Side Castling"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be3 c6 5.f3 b5 6.Qd2 Nbd7 7.h4
{ Once again, we see White sending their h-pawn to attack our fianchetto
structure. And of course, we let them know we also have an h-pawn. } 7...h5
{ Now, we continue with the same ideas fromchapter 2! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Neutralizing the h-pawn Attack"]
[Black "Nepomniachtchi, I. vs. Nyback, T. Champion's Challenge, 2023"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be3 c6 5.f3 b5 6.Qd2 Nbd7 7.h4
{ Imagine you are facing an elite player as strong as GM Ian Nepomniachtchi
and he quickly plays h4. What to do? Of course, the same recipe! } 7...h5
{ Nepo, just go home! } 8.Nh3 Bg7 9.Ng5
{ Same idea by White. They have to place a piece on the g5-square to feel
better about their h4-push. } 9...Qc7 10.Rd1 a6 11.a3 Bb7 12.Kf2
{ White is castling by foot, but they are going to the kingside. That means
our king is actually safe castling kingside. } 12...c5 13.d5 Ne5 14.Kg1 Bc8
{ Our bishop looks for a better diagonal. } 15.g3 O-O
{ And Black ended up winning this game. The rest of the game is not
relevant to our course, but you can certainly find it on the internet if
you'd like to see how it ended. } *

