[Black "Pirc vs. Byrne Variation Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5
{ The starting variation of the Byrne Variation. } 4...Bg7
{ This is known as the Byrne variation and I have good news and bad news
for you. Bad news is that it is dangerous and easy to encounter at the
beginner and intermediate levels. Good news is that you already know how to deal with it. We will continue with ...c6 creating our own leverage pawn
to attack on the queenside. Let's see. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Pirc vs. Byrne Variation"]
[Black "Byrne Variation: 5.Qd2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5
{ The starting variation of the Byrne Variation. } 4...Bg7
{ In case White captures our f6-knight, we have to be ready to recapture
with our bishop instead of pawn. } 5.Qd2
{ This is why I said you already know how to deal with it. White is ready
to castle queenside and attack us heavily when we castle kingside. Never
forget that any time White shows intentions to adopt this plan, we react quickly on the queenside and delay kingside castling. }
5...c6 { Say hello to ourleverage pawn! } 6.O-O-O b5
{ Let's go for their king before they get to ours. } 7.Bd3 Nbd7 8.Bh6 Bxh6
{ Since we are not going to castle kingside, we take their bishop. } 9.Qxh6
Qa5
{ Now we are ready to play ...b4 followed by ...Qxa2. Also, if our king
feels compromised in the center, we can quickly bring it to the queenside
with ...Bb7 and ...O-O-O. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Pirc vs. Byrne Variation"]
[Black "Byrne Variation: 5.e5 Nfd7 6.exd6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5
{ The starting variation of the Byrne Variation. } 4...Bg7
{ In case White captures our f6-knight, we have to be ready to recapture
with our bishop instead of pawn. } 5.e5
{ This is the tricky move in the Byrne variation. What? The premature e5?
Yes, this time the a1-rook is protecting the white Queen
[because their queenside bishop already moved to g5]. So, trading pawns on e5 followed by the trade of queens on d1 would
only activate their rook. } 5...Nfd7
{ If we cannot take on e5, then we have to move our knight. From d7, we are
safely targeting White's e5-pawn with the help of our d6-pawn and
g7-bishop. Also, thanks to their bishop being on g5, we can play the powerful ...f6 move. }
6.exd6 cxd6 7.Qd2 { The white queen gets in position for aggressive play. }
7...Qa5 { Of course our queen follows suit. } 8.O-O-O
{ At this point, it's all set and our main focus is mobilizing forces to
attack the white king. } 8...Nc6 9.Nf3 Nb6
{ Our knight moves towards the objective and opens up our undeveloped
c8-bishop. } 10.Bh6 Bxh6
{ We are not afraid of the white queen landing on h6 since we are not going
to castle kingside anyway. After 11.Qxh6 Be6 , we are fully developed and
ready to attack the white king. We can always castle queenside if necessary. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Pirc vs. Byrne Variation"]
[Black "Byrne Variation: 5.e5 Nfd7 6.f4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg5
{ The starting variation of the Byrne Variation. } 4...Bg7
{ In case White captures our f6-knight, we have to be ready to recapture
with our bishop instead of pawn. } 5.e5
{ This is the tricky move in the Byrne variation. What? The premature e5?
Yes, this time the a1-rook is protecting the white Queen
[because their queenside bishop already moved to g5]. So, trading pawns on e5 followed by the trade of queens on d1 would
only activate their rook. } 5...Nfd7
{ If we cannot take on e5, then we have to move our knight. From d7, we are
safely targeting White's e5-pawn with the help of our d6-pawn and
g7-bishop. Also, thanks to their bishop being on g5, we can play the powerful ...f6 move. }
6.f4
{ This setup is very rare, but we have to learn how to deal with it. Don't
worry! If you remember the ...f6 break, you will be fine. After all, it's
about targeting White's center. However, we need to get our king away from the center before it opens up. }
6...O-O 7.Nf3 f6
{ Inevitably the position will open up and the white king is the one stuck
in the center. } 8.exf6 exf6 9.Bc4+ Kh8 10.Bh4 Nb6
{ Our knight is improved with a tempo on the c4-bishop. Once White takes
care of their hanging bishop, we finish development. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Pirc vs. Austrian Attack"]
[Black "Pirc vs. Austrian Attack Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B09"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f4
{ What's better than two pawns in the center? Yes, you guessed it —three
pawns in the center. That's White's philosophy when they play the Austrian
attack. Black has several ways to deal with such a big center and as long as we keep our hypermodern spirit, we will be fine. The great Bobby
Fischer used the Austrian Attack often and that contributed to its popularity. So, we better get ready for it! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Pirc vs. Austrian Attack"]
[Black "Austrian Attack: 5.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B09"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f4
{ This is officially the Austrian Attack. And yes, it looks scary. White is
letting Black know they can now play e5 anytime they like. Good news for us
is that, as usual, White's e5 push is not dangerous. } 4...Bg7
{ Since there is nothing we can do to prevent the e4-pawn from advancing,
we simply continue with our normal development. } 5.e5
{ Inexperienced players won't be able to control themselves. So, we have to
review this early aggression. } 5...dxe5
{ Our d-pawn has been waiting for this opportunity since move one. } 6.dxe5
Qxd1+
{ We already now what happens when White recaptures on e5 with their
d-pawn. The d-file opens and we immediately take their queen. Now they have
to compromise one of their pieces. } 7.Nxd1
{ 7.Kxd1 would lose White the right to castle. Black can continue with
7...Ng4 threatening to land on the f2-square with a lethal fork. } 7...Nd5
{ Since the white knight left, we have the central d5-square for ourselves.
} 8.Nf3 O-O { Now it's a matter of developing our queenside. } *

