1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f4
{ This is officially the Austrian Attack. And yes, it looks scary. White is
letting Black know they can now play e5 anytime they like. Good news for us
is that, as usual, White's e5 push is not dangerous. } 4...Bg7
{ Since there is nothing we can do to prevent the e4-pawn from advancing,
we simply continue with our normal development. } 5.e5
{ Inexperienced players won't be able to control themselves. So, we have to
review this early aggression. } 5...dxe5
{ Our d-pawn has been waiting for this opportunity since move one. } 6.fxe5
{ White decided to keep two pawns in the center anyways. They also
prevented Black from taking their queen. However, now our f6-knight can
safely move to the central d5-square. } 6...Nd5 7.Nxd5
{ White takes us before we take them. } 7...Qxd5 8.Nf3 c5
{ You should be familiar with these kinds of moves by now. We want to trade
one of White's central pawns for one of our flank pawns. Soon, we will be
castling and finishing development on the queenside. } 9.c4 Qe4+
{ Getting away from White's threat by gaining a tempo on their king. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
