[White "4) Pirc vs. Austrian Attack"]
[Black "Austrian Attack: 5.Nf3 O-O 6.e5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B09"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f4
{ This is officially the Austrian Attack. And yes, it looks scary. White is
letting Black know they can now play e5 anytime they like. Good news for us
is that, as usual, White's e5 push is not dangerous. } 4...Bg7 5.Nf3
{ White understands the importance of keeping the central pawns next to
each other and waits for a better time to execute their ...e5 push. } 5...O-O
{ Now that our king is castled, we are ready to fight for the initiative. }
6.e5
{ I know you don't need this information by now, but we still have to cover
it. We treat this early attack the same way we would if they played it one
move earlier. Among other things, notice how the d5-square is now available to our f6-knight. }
6...dxe5 7.fxe5
{ The alternative would be 7.dxe5 Qxd1+ 8.Nxd1 Nd5 or 7.dxe5 Qxd1+ 8.Kxd1
Rd8+ 9.Ke1 Nd5 . } 7...Nd5 8.Nxd5 Qxd5 9.c4 Qe4+
{ Getting away from White's threat by gaining a tempo on their king. } 10.Be2
Nc6
{ Happy to develop by adding more pressure to White's central pawns. Next,
we want to develop our c8-bishop and place one of our rooks on the d-file.
} *

