1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f4
{ This is officially the Austrian Attack. And yes, it looks scary. White is
letting Black know they can now play e5 anytime they like. Good news for us
is that, as usual, White's e5 push is not dangerous. } 4...Bg7 5.Nf3
{ White understands the importance of keeping the central pawns next to
each other and waits for a better time to execute their ...e5 push. } 5...O-O
{ Now that our king is castled, we are ready to fight for the initiative. }
6.Be3
{ From White's perspective, this move seems very natural. For a hypermodern
player, it is a unique opportunity to fight for the initiative. } 6...Ng4
{ We quickly target that hanging bishop on e3 and open our own fianchettoed
bishop from g7. What a subtle way to disguise our true objective! } 7.Qd2
{ Some players might want to preserve their dark-squared bishop with 7.Bd2
, but then we can reply with 7...c5 striking the center and trying to open
up our fianchettoed bishop from g7. } 7...e5
{ As much as we would like to eliminate their e3-bishop, there is no rush.
We cannot forget the ...e5 break to claim our share of the center. } 8.dxe5
dxe5 9.fxe5 Nxe3 10.Qxe3 Bg4
{ Look at White's central pawns. They are weak and we will take on e5
sooner or later. } *

