1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.f4
{ This is officially the Austrian Attack. And yes, it looks scary. White is
letting Black know they can now play e5 anytime they like. Good news for us
is that, as usual, White's e5 push is not dangerous. } 4...Bg7 5.Nf3
{ White understands the importance of keeping the central pawns next to
each other and waits for a better time to execute their ...e5 push. } 5...O-O
{ Now that our king is castled, we are ready to fight for the initiative. }
6.Bd3
{ Here is another natural move that supports the white center while leaving
everything ready to castle. } 6...Nc6
{ We saw a similar idea against Bd3 in the classical variation. Our
c6-knight is ready to support thethematic ...e5 push by Black. What if
White's d-pawn advances to attack our knight? Well, same treatment we gave their dark-squared bishop when it moved to e3 in the other line. }
7.d5 Nb4
{ The annoying knight jumps to attack White's d3-bishop. We were familiar
with this resource already, but I still wanted to remind you this is why we
were okay with 6...Nc6 in the first place. } 8.Be2 c6
{ Even if we cannot capture their bishop, moving our knight gave us another
resource —attacking their central pawn with our flank pawn. } 9.a3 Na6
10.Bxa6 bxa6
{ Don't worry about our c6-pawn. 11.dxc6 Qb6 and we get our pawn back. From
b6, the black queen is very powerful, especially if we manage to bring our
knight to g4 in the future. } *

