1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.g3 Bg7
{ The starting position of the Fianchetto Variation. } 5.Bg2 O-O
{ Now that the black king is castled, we get ready to unleash our
hypermodern magic! } 6.Nf3
{ So, what should a hypermodern player like you play here? Black simply
wants their e5 break in the center. Can we play ...Nc6 first? If 6...Nc6 ,
White can attack our knight by advancing their d-pawn 7.d5 and then we don't have a good square to go to. What? Why can't our knight jump to e5?
7...Ne5 Because of their f3-knight! We would like to avoid doubled pawns. Got it! }
6...Bg4
{ I know you didn't need any help to think of this plan! Now Black is ready
to claim their share of the center by playing ...e5. } 7.h3 Bxf3 8.Qxf3 Nc6
{ At this point, we are fully developed and ready to strike the center with
...e5. Here I recommend 8...Nc6 because Black completes development with a
tempo on the d4-pawn. However, 8...Nfd7 or 8...c6 are probably more accurate. Just feel free to try them all and pick the one you like the most. }
9.Be3
{ The alternative would be 9.d5 Ne5 10.Qe2 c6 as we have seen in the
classical variation. } 9...e5 { Welcome to your hypermodern territory! }
10.d5
{ The alternative would have been 10.dxe5 dxe5 and Black has a comfortable
position. } 10...Nd4
{ The annoying black knight lands in the center with serious threats hoping
White captures it, opening up the center. } *

