[Black "Fianchetto Variation: 6.Nge2 e5 7.O-O"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.g3 Bg7
{ The starting position of the Fianchetto Variation. } 5.Bg2 O-O
{ Now that the black king is castled, we get ready to unleash our
hypermodern magic! } 6.Nge2
{ This time, White develops their kingside knight to e2 instead of f3 in
order to not block their fianchetto bishop from g2. } 6...e5
{ Of course! Without the white knight on f3, we are free to play ...e5
right away. Now White can take, advance or leave it up to us. Let's review
them one by one. } 7.O-O exd4 { If they don't take us, we take them! } 8.Nxd4
Nc6
{ This is my favorite way to continue, but we can always play 8...Bd7 first
and only then we develop our knight to c6. } 9.Nxc6 bxc6
{ Now you can appreciate why I don't mind getting a bad pawn structure on
the queenside. Thanks to it, we have more control over the d5 and b5
squares. We also get the b-file for our a8-rook. } *

