1.e4 d6 2.Bc4
{ This move is not new to us. However, with this move order, it can lead to
a specific setup that many Pirc Defense players find annoying. } 2...Nf6
{ Yes, we continue with our setup! } 3.d3
{ Such an innocent move, right? So, Black continues. } 3...g6 4.f4
{ What? Is this the Austrian Attack? No! White's d-pawn is on d3 instead of
d4. Ok! Is it dangerous? Only if Black underestimates the powerful
c4-bishop. For now, we complete kingside development. } 4...Bg7 5.Nc3 O-O
{ Kingside is complete! } 6.Nf3
{ It's time to pick the right plan from our toolbox. This time, we are
going after the c4-bishop. } 6...Nc6
{ Our knight is ready to go to a5 in order to eliminate White's powerful
bishop. Now you only need to know what to do when they allow it and when
they don't. } 7.O-O
{ If White doesn't play 7.a3 to hide their bishop on a2, we immediately go
after it. } 7...Na5 8.Bb3
{ White can also leave their bishop on c4 with 8.Qe1 Nxc4 9.dxc4 c6 10.Qh4
b5 11.cxb5 cxb5 12.Be3 12.Nxb5 loses to 12...Qb6+ 12...b4 13.Nd5 Nxd5
14.exd5 Bf5 and Black is in good shape. } 8...Nxb3 { Good bye bishop! }
9.axb3 a6
{ White lost their powerful bishop, but their a1-rook is now activated. So,
it's good to keep our a-pawn safe. } 10.h3 b6
{ Black's bishop is headed for b7 giving us good control over the long
diagonals [a1-h8 and h1-a8]. However, without
our bishop on c8, we lose control over the f5-square and White could play f5 at any moment. For that reason, I would play ...e6 before ...Bb7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pirc vs. Harmonist Variation"]
[Black "Harmonist Variation: 5.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B00"]

1.e4 d6 2.Bc4
{ This move is not new to us. However, with this move order, it can lead to
a specific setup that many Pirc Defense players find annoying. } 2...Nf6
{ Yes, we continue with our setup! } 3.d3
{ Such an innocent move, right? So, Black continues. } 3...g6 4.f4
{ What? Is this the Austrian Attack? No! White's d-pawn is on d3 instead of
d4. Ok! Is it dangerous? Only if Black underestimates the powerful
c4-bishop. For now, we complete kingside development. } 4...Bg7 5.Nc3 O-O
{ Kingside is complete! } 6.Nf3
{ It's time to pick the right plan from our toolbox. This time, we are
going after the c4-bishop. } 6...Nc6
{ Our knight is ready to go to a5 in order to eliminate White's powerful
bishop. Now you only need to know what to do when they allow it and when
they don't. } 7.a3
{ With this clever move, White can always put their c4-bishop on a2. }
7...Bg4
{ With the ...Na5 plan out of the picture, we look inside our toolbox again
and this time we pick my favorite ...Bg4. With the f3-knight neutralized,
our c6-knight can land on the d4-square. } 8.h3 Bxf3 9.Qxf3 Nd4
{ I don't know about you, but I get a great feeling when I play a move like
this one. } 10.Qf2 c5
{ Yes, you could have played 10...Nd7 opening our fianchetto bishop from
g7, but I like 10...c5 better in this position. Partly because it will help
you remember what Black's middlegame plan is about. Since our central pawn chain [e7-d6-c5] is aiming at the queenside
we should expand there. A possible continuation could be 11.Be3 b5 [beautiful move] 12.Bxb5 Qb6 and Black either collects the b5-bishop or the b2 pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pirc vs. Harmonist Variation"]
[Black "Harmonist Variation: 5.e5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B00"]

1.e4 d6 2.Bc4
{ This move is not new to us. However, with this move order, it can lead to
a specific setup that many Pirc Defense players find annoying. } 2...Nf6
{ Yes, we continue with our setup! } 3.d3
{ Such an innocent move, right? So, Black continues. } 3...g6 4.f4
{ What? Is this the Austrian Attack? No! White's d-pawn is on d3 instead of
d4. Ok! Is it dangerous? Only if Black underestimates the powerful
c4-bishop. For now, we complete kingside development. } 4...Bg7 5.e5
{ At this point in the course, we know this e5-push is not White's best
option. However, we still need to be familiar with it when combined with
the powerful c4-bishop. } 5...dxe5
{ Our d-pawn has been waiting for this opportunity since move one. } 6.fxe5
Ng4
{ Our knight goes to the aggressive g4-square as we've seen in other
variations. Now, White has to protect their e5-pawn. } 7.d4
{ It's time to reach into our toolbox again. What move do we use to break
White's center apart [or at least try]. } 7...c5
{ We challenge White's central pawn with our flank pawn. If the d4-pawn
moves, then their e5-pawn falls. } 8.c3 cxd4 9.cxd4 O-O
{ Putting our king in safety before taking another blow at White's center.
} 10.Nf3 Nc6
{ Our c6-knight and queen are putting pressure on the d4-pawn and soon
we'll have our g4 knight landing on f5 [via h6]
with even more pressure. Yes, the hypermodern approach in full effect! } *

