[Black "KID vs. Classical Variation Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E90"]

1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.Nf3 O-O
{ Welcome to the Classical Variation! What? How? Didn't we already cover
this? No! This time we are playing King's Indian Defense
[against 1. d4]. What's the difference? White's c-pawn is on c4 instead of c2. That's why I said you must be able to
tell when we are playing Pirc Defense [against 1. e4] and when we are playing King's Indian Defense [against 1. d4 or anything that is not 1. e4] }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) KID vs. Classical Variation"]
[Black "Classical Variation: 8.dxe5 "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E91"]

1.d4
{ White starts with their queen's pawn and believe it or not, this changes
things a bit. There is no need to worry since we will be adopting the same
setup. However, you must learn to distinguish when you are playing against 1. e4 [Pirc Defense] and when you are facing
something else [King's Indian Defense]. } 1...d6
{ Whenever White does not start with 1.e4, Black likes to play 1...Nf6.
After all, that's what the hypermodern approach is all about and now we can
do it without the e4-pawn ready to attack our knight. With that said, you and I will stick to 1...d6. Why? 1] consistency
2] playing 1...Nf6 now allows White to play the annoying 2.Bg5 move [we will talk more about it soon]. Do note, though, that both move-orders are possible, and very often lead totranspositions. For example,
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 leads to the same position as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 d6 . }
2.c4
{ Most 1. d4 players will play 2. c4 since it strengthens White's control
over the center. Notice how in our lines against 1. e4 White's c-pawn would
remain on c2. Here it's a crucial part of their setup. } 2...Nf6 3.Nc3 g6
4.e4 Bg7 5.Nf3 { The starting position of the Classical Variation. } 5...O-O
{ Still, the classical variation means no stress. So we take a moment to
castle. } 6.Be2
{ Notice how this bishop could only be developed to e2 or d3. There is no
Bc4 this time because of their c-pawn. } 6...Nbd7
{ Just like we do against theLondon System which we will see later. Our
queenside knight is developed to d7. From there, it can easily support our
...e5 break. } 7.O-O
{ White's e5 push would only get them in trouble after 8.e5 dxe5 9.dxe5 Ng4
and their e5 pawn is heavily attack by our two knights and the g7-bishop. }
7...e5
{ Mission accomplished! Now White can capture, push or maintain the
pressure in the center. } 8.dxe5 dxe5 9.Be3 c6
{ Our thematic ...c6 keeps the c3-knight away from d5 and b5. } 10.Qc2 Qe7
{ Our main plan now is to transfer our d7-knight to c5 and then to e6. From
there, it's ready to jump to the attractive d4 or f4 squares. It could be
something like 11.Rad1 Re8 12.h3 Nc5 13.b4 Ne6 [ready to land on d4 or f4] and if 14.Nxe5 Qxb4 Black has a good position. }
*

