1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.f3
{ We are now facing the dangerous Sämisch Variation. Did you notice the
leverage pawn on f3? Yes, we have seen this before. White intends to castle
queenside and launch an aggressive attack on the kingside where they expect us to castle. }
5...c6
{ No way! Do we treat it the same way we do in the Pirc Defense vs.
Opposite-Side Attack? Yes, but since they have a pawn on c4, we cannot play
b5 safely yet. So, we need a second leverage pawn. } *

