[White "8) KID vs. Opposite-Castle Attack"]
[Black "Opposite-Side Attack: 8.O-O-O"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E80"]

1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.f3
{ The starting position of the Sämisch Variation. } 5...c6
{ No way! Do we treat it the same way we do in the Pirc Defense vs.
Opposite-Side Attack? Yes, but since they have a pawn on c4, we cannot play
...b5 safely yet. So, we need a second leverage pawn. } 6.Be3 a6
{ Now we are ready to expand on the queenside with ...b5. } 7.Qd2 b5
{ With such a head start on the queenside, White will think twice before
castling there. } 8.O-O-O
{ White ignores our warning. Now it's all about attacking their king with
everything we got. } 8...Qa5 { Our most powerful piece just checked in! }
9.Kb1 Nbd7 10.g4 Rb8
{ At this point, we are ready to incorporate our b8-rook to the attack. It
will be a sharp middlegame, but we have good attacking chances. It's all
about getting to their king before they get to ours. } *

