1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.f3
{ The starting position of the Sämisch Variation. } 5...c6
{ No way! Do we treat it the same way we do in the Pirc Defense vs.
Opposite-Side Attack? Yes, but since they have a pawn on c4, we cannot play
...b5 safely yet. So, we need a second leverage pawn. } 6.Be3 a6
{ Now we are ready to expand on the queenside with ...b5. } 7.Qd2 b5
{ With such a head start on the queenside, White will think twice before
castling there. } 8.cxb5 { Of course White can capture on b5. } 8...axb5
{ Black is happy to open the a-file for their rook. They basically
activated that a8-rook without moving it. } 9.Bd3 O-O
{ Aren't we supposed to delay castling kingside? With our pawn on b5 and
the powerful a8-rook, White is pretty much forced to castle kingside. So,
we are safe. } 10.Nge2 Nbd7
{ Black is now ready to strike the center with ...e5 or ...c5. Pushing the
b-pawn is also in the air. } *

