[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) KID vs. Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "KID vs. Averbakh Variation Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E73"]

1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.Be2 O-O 6.Bg5 Nbd7
{ Say hello to the Averbakh variation! It's named after the legendary
grandmaster Yuri Averbakh. I don't think you will see it much at the
beginner or intermediate level, but if you ever do, you must be able to classify it correctly. Classify it correctly? What do you mean? Well, is
this a quiet setup like the Classical variation or is it aggressive like theSämisch? The Averbakh variation is an aggressive setup and we must treat it as such. How? By using the same plan we play against the Sämisch, which includes ...c6-...a6-...b5 in case they castle
opposite-side. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) KID vs. Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "Averbakh Variation "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E73"]

1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.Be2
{ Every time I see this move, my antenna goes up. Sometimes they continue
with 6. Nf3 and it stays in the classical variation [quiet
approach]. However, White can also continue with 6. h4 intending 7. h5, which is an aggressive approach. }
5...O-O
{ Even though my antenna is up, I'm not concerned yet. 6.h4 would be met by
6...h5 while 6.Nf3 stays in the Classical Variation. } 6.Bg5
{ This is officially the Averbakh variation. White wants to put their queen
on d2 followed by queenside castling and an aggressive pawn storm on the
kingside. How should we respond? } 6...Nbd7
{ Yes, the same Nbd7! Black is controlling the e5-square and ready to
replace their f6-knight with another knight. } 7.Qd2
{ Okay! White just revealed their aggressive intentions. They are
opposite-side castling and coming for our king. } 7...c6
{ Black adopts the same plan we saw in theKID vs. Sämisch Variation
chapter. The rest should be easy for you to remember. } 8.h4 a6
{ We are now ready to play ...b5. However, you can also play 8...h5 to stop
White's h-pawn. } 9.g4
{ 9.h5 b5 10.hxg6 fxg6 is another option where Black is in good shape
thanks to their open f-file. } 9...b5
{ Black's b-pawn is ready to attack the c3-knight followed by ...Nxe4. }
10.f3 { White protects their e4-pawn. } 10...h5
{ Now that our queenside expansion is in motion, it's a good idea to stop
White's h-pawn. With that said, I also like 10...Qa5 . Black's main task
now is to target the white king. Since it's still in the center, we want to play e5 to open up lines there. If it castles queenside, then we focus on
that part of the board. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) KID vs. Averbakh Variation"]
[Black "Example: Elod Kovacs vs. Sandor Videki, 1999"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E73"]

1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.Be2 O-O 6.Bg5
{ This is officially the Averbakh variation. White wants to put their queen
on d2 followed by queenside castling and an aggressive pawn storm on the
kingside. How should we respond? } 6...Nbd7
{ Yes, the same Nbd7! Black is controlling the e5-square and ready to
replace their f6-knight with another knight. } 7.Qd2
{ Okay! White just revealed their aggressive intentions. They are
opposite-side castling and coming for our king. } 7...c6
{ Black adopts the same plan we saw in theKID vs. Sämisch Variation
chapter. The rest should be easy for you to remember. } 8.h4 a6
{ We are now ready to play ...b5. However, you can also play 8...h5 to stop
White's h-pawn. } 9.O-O-O
{ All the cards are on the table. Now Black must find ways to expose and
attack the white king. Of course, White will try to do the same to the
black monarch. } 9...b5 10.f3 Qa5
{ You should be familiar with this move already. Our most powerful attacker
is in position. } 11.h5 e5
{ Unfortunately, Black underestimated their own ...b4-push followed by
...Qxa2. It would have been crushing in this position. } 12.hxg6 fxg6
{ Taking with the f-pawn activates the f8-rook while opening an escape
window for our king. } 13.d5 b4 14.Nb1 cxd5
{ Opening the c-file to attack the white king. I know you can already see a
black rook landing on c8. } 15.cxd5 Bb7 16.b3 Rac8+
{ Black made contact with the enemy king first. That's what opposite-side
castling attack is all about! } 17.Bc4 Nb6
{ Black won't stop until they get to the White king! } 18.Qd3 Nxc4 19.bxc4
Qxa2 20.Nd2 Nd7
{ Black knows the importance of bringing more attackers towards the white
king. However, 20...Rxc4+ 21.Nxc4 Rc8 was stronger. } 21.Qb1 Qa5
{ Generally, the defender [White in this case]
wants to trade down pieces while the attacker [Black in this
case] needs all their pieces for a more effective attack. }
22.Be3 Qa3+
{ Now Black will capture the e3-bishop. So, White resigned. I hope this
game illustrates what we look for in this kind of middlegame positions. Of
course, things will not always go our way, but the more we expose ourselves to these sharp plans, the better we'll become. }
*

