[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) KID vs. Four Pawns Attack"]
[Black "Example: Kayden Troff vs. Daniel Naroditsky, US Junior Championship, 2011"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E76"]


{ Before we start learning the setup I recommend against this variation,
let's see how GM Daniel Narodistky used the ...Bg4 plan we covered in the
Pirc Defense. As long as we understand the plans and ideas we have already discussed, we can deal with anything. }
1.d4 g6
{ Daniel started with 1...g6 instead of 1...d6 and it's perfectly fine.
Move order is not that important as long as we know where our pieces go. }
2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 d6 4.e4 Nf6 5.f4
{ We are officially facing the Four Pawns Attack. From White's perspective,
they have solid control over the center. The more the merrier! Black thinks
those four pawns are liabilities White cannot maintain for long. Sometimes more is less! From now on, both players will try to prove each other wrong.
} 5...Bg4
{ If you already went over our Pirc Defense lines [vs.
e4], you should be familiar with this move. Even though it's
not the best choice in this position, Black knows their plan and that's what matters. }
6.Qb3 Nc6
{ Yes, we know this knight loves the c6-square and we often see it happen
in the ...Bg4 lines. } 7.Be3 e5
{ What did I say? You are more than familiar with all of this hypermodern
ideas. } 8.Qxb7 exd4 { Fork! } 9.Nb5 O-O
{ With our king in safety, we are ready to attack. } 10.Qxc6 dxe3 11.Nc3 Rb8
{ Without our b-pawn, we get to put pressure down the b-file. } 12.Be2 Rxb2
13.O-O-O Qb8
{ With kings castled opposite side, we know we must attack theirs before
they attack ours. As you can see, the b-file is our way in. } 14.h3 Nxe4
{ Narodistky remembered his powerful bishop is fianchettoed on g7 and now
it's too much for the White king. } 15.Nxe4 Rb1+ 16.Kc2 Qb2+ 17.Kd3 Qa3+
18.Nc3 Qxc3+ 19.Ke4 f5+ 20.Kd5 Rxd1+
{ White resigned here, but let me show you why. } 21.Bxd1 Qd4+ 22.Ke6 Qf6+
23.Kd5 { 23.Kd7 Qf7 is also checkmate. } 23...Qf7# *

