1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.f4
{ We are officially facing the Four Pawns Attack. From White's perspective,
they have solid control over the center. The more the merrier! Black thinks
those four pawns are liabilities White cannot maintain for long. Sometimes more is less! From now on, both players will try to prove each other wrong.
} 5...O-O
{ Black puts their king in safety before striking the center. They
understand it can get messy. } 6.e5
{ As you probably suspect, this early e5 push cannot be good for White. }
6...dxe5 { Our d-pawn was waiting for this moment. } 7.fxe5 Nfd7
{ Our knight was under attack and from d7, we are both attacking the
aggressive ...e5 pawn and supporting our own ...c5 break. Don't forget it's
all about White's central pawns. } 8.Nf3 c5
{ The final strike to break down White's center. } 9.dxc5
{ Without a pawn on d4, the aggressive e5-pawn is hanging. } 9...Nxe5
{ Yes, mission accomplished! White's center is not what it used to be and
their king is still in the center. Also, their pawns on the c-file are in
bad shape. } *

