1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.f4
{ We are officially facing the Four Pawns Attack. From White's perspective,
they have solid control over the center. The more the merrier! Black thinks
those four pawns are liabilities White cannot maintain for long. Sometimes more is less! From now on, both players will try to prove each other wrong.
} 5...O-O
{ Black puts their king in safety before striking the center. They
understand it can get messy. } 6.e5
{ As you probably suspect, this early e5 push cannot be good for White. }
6...dxe5 { Our d-pawn was waiting for this moment. } 7.dxe5
{ When White recaptures with their d-pawn, the d-files opens. Now, we trade
queens! } 7...Qxd1+ 8.Nxd1
{ Taking with the king would make White lose the right to castle. If they
did, 8.Kxd1 I would continue with 8...Ng4 threatening 9...Nf2+ with a fork.
} 8...Ne4
{ Since White's knight moved to d1, we can land in the center safely. } 9.Nf3
f6 { Our final blow to destroy what's left of White's central pawns. }
10.exf6 exf6
{ Mission accomplished! White's central pawns are gone and the white king
is still in the center. Now, it's a matter of developing the rest of your
pieces and eventually moving your f-pawn to open the g7-bishop. } *

