1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.e4 Bg7 5.f4
{ We are officially facing the Four Pawns Attack. From White's perspective,
they have solid control over the center. The more the merrier! Black thinks
those four pawns are liabilities White cannot maintain for long. Sometimes more is less! From now on, both players will try to prove each other wrong.
} 5...O-O 6.Nf3
{ White focuses on developing their pieces and castling quickly. That's why
Black must act. } 6...e5
{ Nobody was expecting this! Black meets White's challenge head on. As you
can see in GM Daniel Naroditsky's game, Black has different ways to
proceed. He actually chose the ...Bg4 plan. However, I like this one so much because of a few reasons. a] White's king is still in the
center and we want to open up the game to attack it. b] It has the surprise factor since it seems like Black can never put a pawn on e5 due to White having 3 attackers on that square. c] It gives us exposure to one of the most dynamic approaches a hypermodern player
can adopt. } 7.d5
{ This is very rare, but if White gives us the opportunity to open the
e-file, we take it! } 7...exf4 8.Bxf4 Nxe4
{ Tactics in the air! The white king is in the center and our f8-rook is
ready to take advantage of it. } 9.Nxe4 Re8 10.Bd3 f5
{ The e4-knight cannot move because of the vulnerable white king. Black is
getting their piece back and maintaining the advantage. } *

