{ We are officially facing the Four Pawns Attack. From White's perspective,
they have solid control over the center. The more the merrier! Black thinks
those four pawns are liabilities White cannot maintain for long. Sometimes more is less! From now on, both players will try to prove each other wrong.
} 5...O-O 6.Nf3
{ White focuses on developing their pieces and castling quickly. That's why
Black must act. } 6...e5
{ Nobody was expecting this! Black meets White's challenge head on. As you
can see in GM Daniel Naroditsky's game, Black has different ways to
proceed. He actually chose the ...Bg4 plan. However, I like this one so much because of a few reasons. a] White's king is still in the
center and we want to open up the game to attack it. b] It has the surprise factor since it seems like Black can never put a pawn on e5 due to White having 3 attackers on that square. c] It gives us exposure to one of the most dynamic approaches a hypermodern player
can adopt. } 7.fxe5 { In my opinion, this is the most natural reply. }
7...dxe5
{ Once more, White has to deal with the brave and annoying black pawn on
e5! They have to capture it or advance their d-pawn to prevent Black from
taking on d4. Let's examine these options. } 8.Nxe5
{ Believe it or not, this position is considered to be clearly superior for
Black. How is it possible? They have a powerful pawn center and just won an
enemy pawn. Well, only a hypermodern player can understand. } 8...c5
{ When I said this is the ultimate challenge for a hypermodern player, I
meant it! However, this goes beyond the hypermodern movement. White's king
is in the center and Black must open up lines to attack it. That's a general Chess principle that we must follow regardless of the opening we play.
Now White has a few options. } 9.dxc5
{ This is an exciting but tricky moment. White's knight is hanging on e5.
So, we know we have to have something. However, we must remember the white
king is still in the center and we need as many pieces as possible to attack it —especially our queen. So, how do we put pressure down the e-file
without trading queens? } 9...Qe8 10.Bf4
{ White doesn't want to move their knight from e5, but they can only delay
it for so long. } 10...Nh5
{ At this point, our h5-knight attacks the hanging f4-bishop while both our
fianchettoed bishop and queen attack the e5-knight. } *

