1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.g3
{ The starting position of the Fianchetto Variation. } 5...O-O 6.Bg2 Nbd7
{ Once again, we develop our queenside knight to the comfortable d7-square.
Now we are ready to claim our share of the center with our thematic ...e5
break. } 7.O-O e5
{ Mission accomplished! Now White can capture, push or maintain the
pressure in the center. } 8.dxe5 dxe5
{ It's possible to recapture with the d7-knight too, but I prefer pawn. }
9.e4 c6
{ Once more, Black places a pawn on c6 to keep the c3-knight away while
making the c7-square available for their queen. } 10.Qc2 Qe7
{ Our queen could also go to c7, but I prefer e7 in this line. Next, we
want our d7-knight to go to the attractive d4-square via c5 and e6 or f8
and e6. } *

