1.d4 d6 2.c4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.g3
{ The starting position of the Fianchetto Variation. } 5...O-O 6.Bg2 Nbd7
{ Once again, we develop our queenside knight to the comfortable d7-square.
Now we are ready to claim our share of the center with our thematic ...e5
break. } 7.O-O e5
{ Mission accomplished! Now White can capture, push or maintain the
pressure in the center. } 8.d5
{ You should be more than familiar with this pattern by now. Central pawn
advances? Look for the juicy square! } 8...a5
{ We want to place our d7-knight on c5, but we first prevent White from
kicking it out with their b-pawn. } 9.e4 Nc5
{ Both black knights attack the e4-pawn. } 10.Qc2 Ne8
{ We remove our knight to start the thematic pawn storm on the kingside.
Don't forget our pawn chain in the center is telling us where to expand.
Now, we target the pawn in front of our most forward pawn via f5. } *

