1.d4
{ White starts with their queen's pawn and believe it or not, this changes
things a bit. There is no need to worry since we will be adopting the same
setup. However, you must learn to distinguish when you are playing against 1.e4 [Pirc Defense] and when you are facing
something else [King's Indian Defense]. } 1...d6
{ Whenever White does not start with 1. e4, Black likes to play 1...Nf6.
After all, that's what the hypermodern approach is all about and now we can
do it without the e4-pawn ready to attack our knight. With that said, you and I will stick to 1...d6. Why? 1] consistency
2] playing 1...Nf6 now allows White to play the annoying 2.Bg5 move [we will talk more about it soon]. }
2.Bf4
{ The starting position of the London System. This tame but solid
developing move aims to build a pawn triangle with e3 and c3 with the
dark-squared bishop comfortably outside the pawn chain. Our system does not change against this. }
2...Nf6
{ Here I would still be careful with the possibility of White playing 3.Bg5
. It cannot be right of course since they are moving the same piece twice
with no clear compensation, but it is still possible. Then, if you play 3...g6 4.Bxf6 destroys Black's pawn structure. Nothing serious, but I just
don't like it. So, I would play 2...g6 so that I can meet White's Bg5 with ...Bg7 defending our f6-knight. }
3.Nf3 g6 4.e3 Bg7 5.Bd3
{ White tends to avoid developing their bishop to d3 since it could fall
victim to a fork. Once Black accomplishes their ...e5 push, that same
e-pawn could advance to e4 attacking both the f3-knight and d3-bishop. }
5...O-O
{ See? We simply did what we typically do. With our king castled, now we
think of our queenside pieces and our middlegame plans. } 6.O-O Nbd7
{ Our knight silently moves to d7 in order to support our thematic ...e5
break. Yes, our system is that flexible. What can I tell you? } 7.c3 Re8
{ Our rook joins the d7-knight to finally play ...e5. And yes, this time we
are finally ready! } 8.Nbd2 e5
{ Since the white queen has the d3-bishop and d2-knight in front, it's safe
to play ...e5 now. Please, keep in mind that you can also fianchetto your
c8-bishop first, and only after strike the center with ...e5. Note that here if White is sloppy and plays 9.Bg3 we have afork! 9...e4 ,
double-attacking the white bishop and knight when both cannot be saved. } *

