1.c4
{ The English opening is a legendary setup that you are not likely to
encounter at the beginner level. However, as you move up the ladder, you
will face it and it's good to at least be familiar with it. It's not that tricky mainly because White typically allows Black to do their opening
without any immediate pressure. } 1...d6 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.g3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 5.d3 O-O
{ Notice how White decided to control the center with a flank pawn
[c4]. This means we have no central pawns to
target. However, we continue with our typical plan of claiming our share of the center via ...e5. }
6.Nf3 e5 { This time, it's easy to put our pawn on e5. So, we do it! } 7.O-O
Nc6 { Yes, Black could also move their queenside knight to d7. } 8.Bd2 h6
{ This is a prophylactic move to keep White's pieces from the g5-square.
Now we can continue with either 9...Be6 followed by 10...Qd7 or 9...Nh5
followed by 10...f5. } *

