1.b3
{ An uncommon, but solid starting move. The intention is clear - to develop
the dark-squared bishop on its long diagonal. } 1...g6
{ Yes, different move order. The headline in my mind is fianchetto vs.
fianchetto. } 2.Bb2 Nf6
{ We have to block the b2-bishop and ...Nf6 is a move we do in our system
anyway. } 3.Bxf6
{ White rarely lets go of their powerful fianchetto bishop so easily, but
at the beginner and intermediate levels, it's pretty common. } 3...exf6
{ Capturing on f6 opens the e-file for one of our rooks to attack in the
future. Also, our f6-pawn will move to f5 controlling the e4-square and
leaving the a1-h8 diagonal open for our fianchetto bishop. } 4.d4 Bg7 5.Nf3
O-O 6.e3 f5
{ Problem solved! Our g7-bishop is open and we control the e4-square. } 7.Be2
Re8 8.O-O d6 9.Nbd2 Nd7 { Our knight is headed for the e4-square via f6. }
10.c3 Nf6 { The c8-bishop can be developed via d7 or b7. } *

