1.b3
{ An uncommon, but solid starting move. The intention is clear - to develop
the dark-squared bishop on its long diagonal. } 1...g6
{ Yes, different move order. The headline in my mind is fianchetto vs.
fianchetto. } 2.Bb2 Nf6
{ We have to block the b2-bishop and ...Nf6 is a move we do in our system
anyway. } 3.e3
{ Of course, we have to know what to do when White preserves their
b2-bishop. } 3...Bg7 4.Nf3 d6 5.d4 O-O 6.Be2 Nbd7
{ Once again we see our queenside knight develop to d7. We are getting
ready for our thematic ...e5 push. } 7.O-O b6
{ Double fianchetto? Where have we seen this before? It's the same way we
treat the London System. } 8.c4 Bb7 9.Nbd2
{ 9.Nc3 would block the powerful b2-bishop. } 9...e5
{ Is this safe? Yes, it is! } 10.dxe5 Ng4
{ The e5-pawn cannot move because our fianchetto bishop would take theirs
on b2. Now we have four pieces to recapture with. } *

