{ 1] The early e5-push by White: is a mistake because after
@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/4P3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0
3@@EndFEN@@ 3...dxe5 4.dxe5 Qxd1+ 5.Kxd1 Ng4 Black is attacking both e5 and f2 while the white king lost the right to castle. 2] The
Central Fork: is one of our main plans [seen mainly in the classical variation]. @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2BPP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...Nxe4 destroys White's solid pawn center and 7.Nxe4 would be met by 7...d5 of course.
3] The Bg4 Plan: @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP1b1/2NB1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 1.a3 This plan can be used in many different variations. The idea is to neutralize White's f3-knight. Why? To help the b8-knight. Let me explain! Should the b8-knight be developed to d7 or c6? We use both, but c6 is preferred as it is more aggressive —pressure on the d4-pawn. In an ideal world, we would develop our b8-knight to c6. It's an active square and it attacks the d4-pawn [hypermodern approach]. If White responds to 2...Nc6 with
3.d5 , our knight then would land on the d4 or e5-squares [knights love to be in the center]. The only problem is both the d4 and e5-squares are currently protected by White's f3-knight. I'd like to point out that pinning that f3-knight is enough. We don't have to take it unless they play h3 or break the pin by moving their queen away or playing Be2, for example. 4] White's d5-push: is music to our ears! Automatically the dark squares in the center [d4, e5 and c5] belong to Black. Now we use what I remember as the dark-square strategy. Immediately our c6-knight can jump in the holes - d4 or e5 . @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/3P4/4P3/2NB1Q1P/PPP2PP1/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 1...Ne5 Even the f6-knight can reroute itself via d7 to land on e5 or c5. The fianchetto bishop is also happy to see the a1-h8 diagonal open up. 5] The Nc6 & Bd3 Romance: is real. In this position, we played ...Nc6 even though we cannot jump to the center after White plays d5 [f3-knight's fault]. With the white bishop on d3, however, our knight is happy to hop to
@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/3P4/4P3/2NB1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 1...Nb4 completing its mission: White's center is now weaker [after their d5-push] and we go for their bishop pair. 6] White's d5-pawn: can also be exploited by challenging that d5-pawn [an important central pawn] with our c-pawn with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/3P4/4P3/2NQ3P/PPP2PP1/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@ 1...c6 [less important flank pawn]. 7] Black's @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/3PP3/2NB1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 1...e5 strike: is what we ultimately look for. We allow White to build a solid pawn center for us to target it. However, sooner or later we want to claim our share of the center and e5 is our way to do it. Classical players prefer to put a pawn on e5 since move 1. [e.g. 1.e4 e5]. Hypermodern players like us understand how important it is to place a pawn in the center, but we want to do it whenever we want —later in the game. 8] The c6-pawn: in this kind of position @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3pbp/2p2np1/4p1B1/4P3/2NB3P/PPP2PP1/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ 1.O-O ...c6 is extremely important in our system and it can be used in different ways. One of them is to keep White's c3-knight from landing on the d5 or b5 squares. It also makes the c7-square available for the black queen. 9] Recapturing on e5: has a lot to do with the c-pawn moving to c6. Black always has to be careful with White's c3-knight landing on d5. Our thematic way to deal with it is by placing a pawn on c6. That's why in a position like this one, I would play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2np1np1/4P3/4P3/2NB1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 1...Nxe5 . Then c6 is available for our c-pawn. 10] White keeps central tension: and we don't like it. Once we strike the center with e5, if they don't take us, we take them @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2np1np1/4p3/3PP3/2NBBN1P/PPP2PP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 1...exd4 if possible [there might be some exceptions of course]. 11] The closed center [ e4 , e5 , d5 , d6]: occurs when Black strikes the center with
...e5 and White replies with d5. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pbp/2np1np1/3Pp3/4P3/2NB1N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 1...Ne7 At this point, it's time to pick a flank and attack there! How do we know what flank is best for us? Easy! Our pawn chain is aiming at it. The c7-d6-e5 pawns are pointing towards the kingside. For the most part, Black wants to transfer pieces to the kingside and target the pawn in front of their most forward pawn. In other words, the thematic plan for Black is to make ...f5 happen as we demonstrated in chapter 1. 12] The c6-plan: can be implemented almost any time. We already learned some of the perks of playing @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 1...c6 . However, there is a whole plan behind it. Whenever I don't feel like or can't play the Bg4 or Central Fork plans, I play ...c6 and ...Nbd7 getting ready to strike the center with our thematic ...e5-push. ...Qc7/...Qa5 and ...Re8 can also be included. 13] @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/8/3PP3/2N1B3/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@ 1...c6 the leverage pawn: is all about aggressive play. Whenever we see White prioritizing queenside development [Be3 or Bf4] over kingside development, it means they might castle long [...O-O-O] and start a pawn storm towards our kingside. Moving the f-pawn to f3 is another signal. As a result, we should delay castling kingside. We don't want White to checkmate us there. Instead we expand on the queenside where White might end up castling - chapter 3. 14] The Austrian Attack: offers White three pawns in the center and their early e5-push might seem scary. However, every time a pawn is moved in Chess, weaknesses are created and that's why Black is happy to take @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/4P3/3P1P2/2N5/PPP3PP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@ 1...dxe5 by occupying the d5 or e4 squares with our f6-knight. 15] The Austrian Attack: without an early e5 by White is possible too. In that case, we castle and use our knights to pressure White. When their bishop is developed to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2N2N2/PPP3PP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 1.Be3 , Black plays ...Ng4 with ideas of ...e5. 16] The Austrian Attack vs. d3-bishop: When their bishop is developed to d3, Black plays @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PPP2/2NB1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 1...Nc6 with ideas of ...Nb4 or ...e5. 17] The Mighty g5-bishop: puts instant pressure on our f6-knight. For that reason, we play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/3p1np1/6B1/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 1...Bg7 to free our e-pawn from being the only defender. We often continue with the c6 leverage pawn as White tends to castle queenside and attack us on the kingside. 18] The annoying c4-bishop: must be eliminated in this setup. That's where ...Nc6 comes handy. We want to play ...Na5 attacking White's bishop. If White plays @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/2np1np1/8/2B1PP2/2NP1N2/PPP3PP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 1.a3 in order to hide their bishop on a2, we then continue aggressively with Bg4 and ...Nd4. 19] The London System: is easy to deal with. Black simply gets ready to strike the center with @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pppnppbp/3p1np1/8/3P1B2/3BPN1P/PPPN1PP1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@ 1...e5 . It's also possible to fianchetto the c8-bishop as well before the thematic ...e5-push. 20] In the KID lines: @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppn1pbp/3p1np1/4p3/2PPP3/2N2N2/PP2BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 1.d5 we often see our queenside knight develop to d7. From there, it supports our thematic ...e5-push and it's ready to land on c5 whenever it becomes available. Black typically plays ...a5 too in order to prevent White's b4-push from kicking our knight out of c5. 21] @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2ppbp/2pp1np1/8/2PPP3/2N1BP2/PP4PP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 1...a6 the leverage pawn: is another way to support the ...b5 expansion. In this position from the Sämisch variation, White is also prioritizing queenside development and Black wants to play ...b5, but due to White's c4-pawn, it's not safe unless ...a6 is played. 22] Four Pawns in The Center: is one of the worst setups White can adopt and Black is not afraid to prove it by breaking it apart immediately with our thematic @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PPPP2/2N2N2/PP4PP/R1BQKB1R b KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 1...e5 push. No preparation is needed as you can see. 23] The English
Opening: is also easy to deal with. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pb1/2np1npp/4p3/2P5/2NP1NPP/PP1BPPB1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 1...Be6 From this simple setup, Black can continue with ...Qd7 and/or prepare the ...f5-push. 24] Harry the h-pawn: is not a problem. Whenever White tries to attack us by playing h4, we can stop it right away by playing @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3PP2P/2N5/PPP1BPP1/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 1...h5 ourselves. 25] The Colle System: is treated similarly to the London System. We can double fianchetto @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p1pn1pbp/1p1p1np1/4p3/2PP4/1P2PN2/PB1NBPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 1...Bb7 and prepare our thematic ...e5-push. In this position, if White plays dxe5, Black has ...Ng4. White's e5-pawn cannot move because our fianchettoed bishop would capture theirs on b2. }
1.-- *

