[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ben Adelson vs. Alexis Mosse, South Florida Grand Prix, 2018"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B00"]


{ In this game, we have one of my former students —Alexis Mosse— playing
the Pirc Defense as Black. Back then, he was around 7 years old. We would
meet once a week for 1 hour and he would play a tournament whenever he could. At the time he played this game, we had been using the formula I
shared with you in theintroduction chapter for a year (around 50 hours) . }
1.e4 d6 2.Bc4 Nf6 3.Qf3
{ It is common to see this move order at the beginner level. They simply
want to execute what's known as Scholar's Mate. The problem is that Black
already has a knight on f6, which makes everything difficult. } 3...g6 4.h3
Bg7 5.g4
{ White is determined to kick the f6-knight out in order to bring their
queen to f7 protected by their c4-bishop with checkmate. } 5...Nc6
{ Black deploys their queenside knight so that it goes after the white
queen. } 6.g5 Nd4
{ Once again, we see the hypermodern approach in action! The black minor
pieces [knights and bishops] start to attack. }
7.Qd3 Nd7
{ Yes, Alexis remembered our brief discussion about the dark squares
strategy. } 8.Nf3 Nc5 9.Qc3
{ The white queen continues to protect the c2-pawn, but e4 is hanging. }
9...Nxe4
{ Both black knights are too powerful now and at the beginner level,
knights are extremely dangerous. } 10.Qd3 Nxf3+ 11.Qxf3 Nxg5 12.Qf4 e5
{ Black attacks the white queen while opening their own. } 13.Qe3 Qf6 14.Nc3
Nf3+ 15.Kf1 Qh4
{ The black queen continues to make its presence known. Now White has to
take care of their c4-bishop and h3-pawn. } 16.Be2 Bxh3+ 17.Rxh3
{ Only move. } 17...Qxh3# { Nice checkmate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jon Ludvig Hammer vs. Magnus Carlsen, Wch. U14, 2003"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A46"]

1.Nf3 d6
{ This game was played years before Magnus became an elite player. However,
it was obvious he would be joining the top soon. Notice how even though
White didn't start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 , he played 1...d6 anyways in order to get
into our opening system. This rare move-order is not covered the course but our approach doesn't change. }
2.d4 Nf6 3.Nbd2 g6 4.e4
{ This is now officially the Pirc Defense. It's the same thing as if White
had played e4 on their first turn. As you can see, Black allows White to
fill the center with two pawns in order to attack them later with pieces and strategic pawn breaks. }
4...Bg7 5.Bd3 O-O
{ Our kingside development is complete! Now it's time to develop our
queenside minor pieces and start targeting White's central pawns. } 6.O-O Nc6
{ The hypermodern approach in action! Magnus is already putting pressure on
the white central pawns from far away. } 7.c3
{ As we will learn in this course, if White pushes their d-pawn 7.d5 , the
c6-knight moves to b4 7...Nb4 attacking the white bishop from d3. } 7...e5
{ The thematic pawn break to claim our share of the center and make the
white central pawns unstable. } 8.h3 Nh5
{ Black's h5-knight is ready to land on f4. Likewise, now the fianchettoed
bishop is open from g7, which puts more pressure on White's d4-pawn
[it's all about White's center]. How can you not like this move? }
9.dxe5 Nf4
{ This kind of move is what separates experienced from inexperienced
players. Black got their knight to a good square with a tempo on the
d3-bishop. They know the e5-pawn is not going anywhere! You know you would have captured on e5 just like me. }
10.Bb5 Nxe5 11.Nxe5 Qg5
{ Once again, Magnus resists his impulse to recapture on e5. Instead, he
improves his powerful queen by threatening checkmate on g2. } 12.Ng4 Qxb5
13.Nb3 Ne2+ 14.Kh1 Bxg4
{ Black develops their last minor piece by exposing the white king. } 15.hxg4
Rae8
{ The only black piece that was doing nothing gets activated by putting
pressure on White's central pawn. } 16.Be3 Rxe4 17.Re1 Qh5+
{ Beautiful queen sacrifice! Once White captures the black queen, the
e4-rook is open to move to h4 with a nice checkmate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nemo Zhou vs. Robert Ramirez, 2022"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be3
{ White chooses an aggressive setup! Luckily, Black has the antidote to it.
} 4...c6
{ We stop everything on the kingside to get ready for an attack on the
queenside since our opponent is likely to castle on that side of the board.
} 5.f3 b5 6.Qd2 Nbd7 7.O-O-O Qa5
{ With the white king committed to the queenside, we have no time to waste.
} 8.Kb1 Nb6 { Every black piece wants to go towards the white king! } 9.Bd3
Nc4 10.Bxc4 bxc4
{ Now the a8-rook can move to b8 to put pressure on the white king. } 11.Qe2
Ba6 12.d5 c5
{ Black knows they have a powerful attack on the queenside. There is no
need to create anything in the center. } 13.Ka1 Rb8 14.Rb1 Bg7
{ We typically develop our dark-squared bishop early in the game. This
time, we waited for the right time. Just look at that a1-h8 diagonal. Our
bishop has to be on it. } 15.Bd2 Rb4 16.Nd1 Qxa2+
{ Nice queen sacrifice. Black is ready to move their b4-rook over to a4
with checkmate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kayden Troff vs. Daniel Naroditsky, US Junior Ch. 2011"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E76"]


{ Before we start learning the setup I recommend against the Four Pawns
Attack, let's see how GM Daniel Narodistky used the Bg4 plan we cover in
the Pirc Defense. As long as we understand the plans and ideas from this course, we can deal with anything. }
1.d4 g6
{ Daniel started with 1...g6 instead of 1...d6 and it's perfectly fine.
Move order is not that important as long as we know where our pieces go. }
2.c4 Bg7 3.Nc3 d6 4.e4 Nf6 5.f4 { The Four Pawns Attack. } 5...Bg4
{ If you already went over our Pirc Defense lines [vs.
e4], you should be familiar with this move. Even though it's
not the best choice in this position, Black knows their plan and that's what matters. }
6.Qb3 Nc6
{ Yes, we know this knight loves the c6-square and we often see it happen
in the ...Bg4 lines. } 7.Be3 e5
{ The thematic ...e5 push to break White's center! Yes, you will see it
over and over. So, pay attention to how Daniel uses it in this game. } 8.Qxb7
exd4 { Fork! } 9.Nb5 O-O { With our king in safety, we are ready to attack. }
10.Qxc6 dxe3 11.Nc3 Rb8
{ Without our b-pawn, we get to put pressure down the b-file. } 12.Be2 Rxb2
13.O-O-O Qb8
{ With kings castled opposite side, we know we must attack theirs before
they attack ours. As you can see, the b-file is our way in. } 14.h3 Nxe4
{ Narodistky remembered his powerful bishop is fianchettoed on g7 and now
it's too much for the White king. } 15.Nxe4 Rb1+ 16.Kc2 Qb2+ 17.Kd3 Qa3+
18.Nc3 Qxc3+ 19.Ke4 f5+ 20.Kd5 Rxd1+
{ White resigned here, but let me show you why. } 21.Bxd1 Qd4+ 22.Ke6 Qf6+
23.Kd5 { 23.Kd7 Qf7 is another checkmate. } 23...Qf7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "KingHuntingMachine vs. Robert Ramirez, Online Game, 2018"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B00"]

1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3
{ A different way to protect the e4-pawn. Something about my beginner
students when they learn a new opening is that they expect their opponents
to play exactly what they learned. However, with so many possible moves in Chess, that's often not the case. }
3...g6
{ Good news is we know where our piece belong regardless of what White
plays [unless they do something aggressive]. }
4.Nf3 Bg7 5.O-O O-O { Kingside development is complete. } 6.Re1 Bg4
{ One of the main plans we cover in this course. And yes, I could have also
played 6...Nc6 or 6...c6 . } 7.h3 Bxf3 8.Qxf3
{ Recapturing with the g-pawn would ruin White's pawn structure and expose
their king. } 8...Nc6 { Again — we develop with a tempo. } 9.c3 e5
{ Opening phase is complete now that we stroke the center with the thematic
...e5 push. } 10.d5
{ The four central pawns are locked. Time to pick your flank and transfer
our knight from the unsafe c6-square to it. } 10...Ne7
{ Getting ready to target the pawn in front of our most forward pawn. } 11.c4
{ White knew these principles too! } 11...Nd7
{ Notice how I moved my knight from f6 to d7 this time. I have also moved
it to e8 in other games. It's mostly a matter of taste. We mainly want to
free our f7-pawn. } 12.Nc3 f5 13.Qd1 f4 14.f3 g5 { Pawn storm! } 15.b4 h5
{ Once we played f4, that f-pawn became our most forward pawn. So, now we
target the white pawn in front of it [f3]. }
16.Bd2 Ng6 { All my pieces want to go to the kingside. } 17.Be2 Nf6
{ Let's go! } 18.a4 Rf7
{ Thematic plan at this point. I want my rook on the same file as the white
king and it also helps my g-pawn break on g4. } 19.c5 Bf8
{ Yes, even our dark-squared bishop that seemed to be bad has an important
role in our plan. It moves to support our center while leaving g7 available
for the f7-rook. } 20.cxd6 cxd6
{ We recapture with a pawn to keep the center locked. } 21.Rc1 Rg7
{ Our maneuver is complete! } 22.Nb5 a6
{ I don't like enemy pieces in my territory. We typically don't move pawns
where we are being attacked, but here it comes with a tempo on the
b5-knight. } 23.Nc3 Nh4 { Our infiltration begins. } 24.Kh1 Qe8
{ Our queen transfers from queenside to kingside. } 25.a5 Qg6
{ The black queen arrived and the party may begin! } 26.Rg1 g4
{ We finally made contact. Black's main objective now is to open up lines
for their pieces to attack. } 27.Be1 g3
{ I know I'm doing the opposite of opening up lines. However, since I'm
familiar with these positions, I knew it was only preparation for the final
blow. } 28.Na4 Nh7
{ My knight is going for the h3 pawn and everybody knows it. That's how we
open the kingside again. } 29.Nb6 Rd8 30.Rc8 Rxc8 31.Nxc8 Ng5
{ It's coming! } 32.Nb6 Nxh3 { I was not kidding. } 33.gxh3
{ Black to move and there is a forced mate in 3 moves. Can you find it? }
33...g2+ 34.Kh2
{ Come on! There is mate in 2 moves now. Did you already see it? } 34...Qg3+
35.Bxg3 fxg3#
{ Checkmate! Our knight protects the g2-pawn while our rook protects the g3
pawn. Besides the interesting mate, pay attention to White's queenside
expansion. It did not succeed because they had to react to our pawn storm on the other flank. }
*

